Hamas‚Äô terrorist assault on Israel will have horrific short- and long-term consequences. As a result of this attack, thousands of Israelis and Palestinians ‚Äì including many women and children ‚Äì have been killed and injured. That toll will rise. The gunning down of young Israelis at a music festival is an image the world will not soon forget. Longer term, this attack is a major setback for any hope of peace and reconciliation in the region ‚Äì and justice for the Palestinian people. For years, people of good will throughout the world, including some brave Israelis, have struggled against the blockade of Gaza, the daily humiliations of occupation in the West Bank, and the horrendous living conditions faced by so many Palestinians. For many, it is no secret that Gaza has been an open-air prison, with millions of people struggling to secure basic necessities. Hamas‚Äô terrorism will make it much more difficult to address that tragic reality and will embolden extremists on both sides, continuing the cycle of violence. Right now, the international community must focus on reducing humanitarian suffering and protecting innocent people on both sides of this conflict. The targeting of civilians is a war crime, no matter who does it. Israel‚Äôs blanket denial of food, water, and other necessities to Gaza is a serious violation of international law and will do nothing but harm innocent civilians. The United States has rightly offered solidarity and support to Israel in responding to Hamas‚Äô attack. But we must also insist on restraint from Israeli forces attacking Gaza and work to secure UN humanitarian access. Let us not forget that half of the two million people in Gaza are children. Children and innocent people do not deserve to be punished for the acts of Hamas.

On this date in 1970, CANNED HEAT debuted at No. 84 on the Billboard Hot 100 with LET'S WORK TOGETHER (Oct 10, 1970) A blues-based rhythm and blues number that made a plea for fidelity in a fractured marriage, 'Let's Stick Together' was written by Wilbert Harrison and released in 1962, Harrison further developed the song and in 1969 when issued it was issued as a two-part single titled "Let's Work Together". Changing the title to "Let's Work Together," Harrison's new message of unity was aimed at a nation rife with conflict over the Civil Rights Movement and the Vietnam War. Shortly after the release of Wilbert Harrison's "Let's Work Together", L.A. blues-rock band Canned Heat recorded their version of the song. Unlike their previous singles ("On the Road Again", "Going Up the Country", and "Time Was") that featured vocals and harmonica by Alan Wilson, for "Let's Work Together" Bob Hite provided the vocals, with Wilson adding the slide-guitar parts. The song was prepared for release as a single in December 1969, but was cancelled due to the popularity of Harrison's single. In the UK, where Harrison's single failed to generate interest, Canned Heat's version was released in January 1970. There it became their biggest hit, reaching number two on the UK Singles chart during a stay of fifteen weeks. Several artists subsequently recorded the songs: "Let's Work Together" by Canned Heat (1970) and "Let's Stick Together" by Bryan Ferry (1976) were both chart successes. Canned Heat didn't mean to overshadow Harrison with their version. In fact, if they'd known the singer was going to have success with it, they never would have recorded it in the first place. They first heard the tune when it was still making the rounds at underground radio stations. Their new guitarist Harvey Mandel played it for the rest of the guys and suggested they cover it, but their co-vocalist, Bob "The Bear" Hite, wanted to wait a few months to see if Harrison would chart first. According to drummer Adolfo de la Parra, Hite didn't like taking songs away from living black musicians unless they weren't hits. "If the song languished among blues collectors, then he thought we could carry it to a bigger audience and at least get the composer writer's royalties," de la Parra wrote in his book, Living The Blues. They recorded the tune in December 1969 without knowing Harrison would get a chart entry just a couple months later. "It was the perfect vehicle for Bob, summoning the world to get together and make someone happy," de la Parra explained. It was his greatest performance and only hit. The song also enhanced Canned Heat's dual character, a band with two lead singers with very different styles and voices.

Ayon kay Lola Patria Millamina, residente ng barangay, nagbigay saya sa kanila ang ELCAC lalo na dahil tumanggap ito ng sampung kilo ng bigas, vitamins for senior citizens good for one month, pati na rin punong itatanim sa kanilang bakuran. Isa si Lola Patria sa 635 na pamilya sa barangay ang binigyan ng Provincial Social Welfare and Development Office (PSWDO) ng family food packs na pakikinabangan ng tinatayang 2,100 na kabuoang bilang ng mga residente dito. Kabilang naman sa pinilahan ngayong araw ay ang rabies vaccination at veterinary health ng Office of the Provincial Veterinarian (OPVet) kung saan abot sa 142 na mga aso at pusa ang nabakunahan ng anti-rabies, at 1,265 ang binigyan ng deworming, 2,187 vitamin supplementation, at 2,385 naman ang binigyan ng treatment medicines. Kasama sa naging benepisyaryo nito ay si Liezl I. Quilakil ng Purok B, Brgy. Ilustre kung saan apat na mga aso at dalawang pusa nito ang nabigyan ng kalinga ng OPVet. Ayon kay Quilakil, malaking tulong para sa kanila na mabigyan ng nabanggit na serbisyo ang kanilang mga alaga dahil abot libo rin ang kailangang gastusin kung pupunta pa sila sa bayan at pribadong veterinary clinic. Sa kabuoan, 175 na mga pet / animal owners ang nakabenepisyo sa naturang programa. Samantala, namahagi rin ang Office of the Provincial Agriculturist ng 117 assorted fruit tree seedlings, 200pcs forest trees para sa tree planting program ng barangay, 6 sacks agricultural salt para sa mga coconut farmers, at technical assistance sa 160 farmers. Katuwang din ng probinsya sa pagbibigay ng tulong sa mga magsasaka ang Metro Arakan Valley Complex na namigay rin ng tig-200 hills iron bamboo, durian (puyat), at grafted calamansi; at hindi pa kasali ang 2,000 tilapia fingerlings, 100 seedlings coconut seedlings , at 100 packs vegetable seeds. Iba't ibang serbisyong medikal rin ang natanggap ng mga residente mula sa Integrated Provincial Health Office (IPHO) katuwang ang rural health unit (RHU) ng bayan tulad ng mga sumusunod: medical consultation, 250; dental services, 32; vitamins for senior citizens, 101; buntis kits, 14; complementary food packs para sa malnourished children, 6; mass feeding, 74; oral health kits for daycare children, 50 at assorted medicines na ibinigay sa barangay council. Namigay rin ang DILG ng 50 school supplies, 50 slippers for children ang PNP, at iba pang mga serbisyo mula sa iba't ibang ahensiya ng pamahalaan. Ang Serbisyong Totoo Caravan ay ipinapatupad ng pamahalaang panlalawigan sa ilalim ng pamumuno ni Gov. Emmylou "Lala" J. God we pray for peace in Israel üôèüèº üáÆüá± What does the Bible say about the conflict in Israel?  Jesus said in Matthew 24, ‚ÄúYou will hear of wars and threats of wars, but don‚Äôt panic. Yes, these things must take place, but the end won‚Äôt follow immediately.  Nation will go to war against nation, and kingdom against kingdom.  There will be famines and earthquakes in many parts of the world.  But all this is only the first of the birth pains, with more to come.  Then you will be arrested, persecuted, and killed. You will be hated all over the world because you are my followers.  And many will turn away from me and betray and hate each other.  And many false prophets will appear and will deceive many people.  Sin will be rampant everywhere, and the love of many will grow cold.  But the one who endures to the end will be saved.‚Äù (Matthew 24:6-13)  

The first thing I notice about this passage is the command of ‚Äúdon‚Äôt panic.‚Äù Our job as Christians is to not be caught up with the rest of the world with the spirit of fear. ‚ÄúGod has not given us a spirit of fear and timidity, but of power, love, and self-discipline.‚Äù (2 Tim. 1:7)  The second thing I notice about this passage is Jesus telling us when we hear of ‚Äúwars and rumors of wars‚Äù that ‚Äúthe end won‚Äôt follow immediately.‚Äù We might be living in the end times, but this is not the end of the end according to Jesus.  The third thing I notice here is Jesus‚Äô stern warning against false prophets.  It‚Äôs easy when there is fear and turmoil to cling to words that make us feel good, but they may not necessarily be what the Bible says.  Beware of false teachers, be grounded in the word of God.  This is no time to follow popular opinions.  This is a time to stand on God‚Äôs word.

So what's our assignment as Christians?
Jesus says in Luke 19:13, "Occupy until I come." The end times are not a time to sit on your rapture rug and wait until Jesus comes back. The end times are for a glorious church to rise and to rule and reign with Christ as "kings and priests unto our God." (Rev. 1:6) Now is the time to take our royal authority over the darkness, to push back the darkness, to contend for souls, to go to war with our prayers and spiritual weapons. Jesus is not coming back for a weak bride. Jesus is coming back for a warrior bride. Now is the time to take authority over the darkness and to push back the gates of hell with our prayers.

So when you hear of wars and rumors of wars, don't panic. Jesus said this is not the end of the end. Occupy until Christ comes. Push back the gates of hell with your prayers and weapons of warfare. Stand on the word and sound doctrine. And remember your prayers are more powerful than you realize. They can pull down the demonic strongholds in the earth, which in turn changes the physical realm. When we go after the kingdom of hell in prayer, we will begin to see the victory in the physical realm as well. Pray for Israel. Pray for the nations of the world. Pray bold prayers and take authority over the dark powers and demons. Christ gave you that authority. The church is the hope of the world. "Upon this rock I will build my church, and all the powers of hell will not conquer it." (Matt. 16:18)

The Middle East Problem, It's Not Complex "When I did my graduate studies at the Middle East Institute at Columbia University‚Äôs School of International Affairs, I took many courses on the question of the Middle East conflict. Semester after semester, we studied the Middle East conflict as if it was the most complex conflict in the world -- when in fact, it is probably the easiest conflict in the world to explain. It may be the hardest to solve, but it is the easiest to explain. In a nutshell, it‚Äôs this: One side wants the other side dead. Israel wants to exist as a Jewish state and to live in peace. Israel also recognizes the right of Palestinians to have their own state and to live in peace. The problem, however, is that most Palestinians and many other Muslims and Arabs, do not recognize the right of the Jewish state of Israel to exist. This has been true since 1947, when the United Nations voted to divide the land called Palestine into a Jewish state and an Arab state. The Jews accepted the United Nations partition but no Arab or any other Muslim country accepted it. When British rule ended on May 15, 1948, the armies of all the neighboring Arab states -- Lebanon, Syria, Iraq, Transjordan, and Egypt -- attacked the one-day old state of Israel in order to destroy it. But, to the world‚Äôs surprise, the little Jewish state survived. Then it happened again. In 1967, the dictator of Egypt, Gamal Abdel Nasser, announced his plan, in his words, ‚Äúto destroy Israel.‚Äù He placed Egyptian troops on Israel‚Äôs border, and armies of surrounding Arab countries were also mobilized to attack. However, Israel preemptively attacked Egypt and Syria. Israel did not attack Jordan, and begged Jordan‚Äôs king not to join the war. But he did. And only because of that did Israel take control of Jordanian land, specifically the ‚ÄúWest Bank‚Äù of the Jordan River. Shortly after the war, the Arab states went to Khartoum, Sudan and announced their famous three ‚ÄúNo‚Äôs: ‚ÄúNo recognition, no peace, and no negotiations,‚Äù What was Israel supposed to do? Well, one thing Israel did, a little more than a decade later, in 1978, was to give the entire Sinai Peninsula -- an area of land bigger than Israel itself, and with oil -- back to Egypt because Egypt, under new leadership, signed a peace agreement with Israel. So, Israel gave land for the promise of peace with Egypt, and it has always been willing to do the same thing with the Palestinians. All the Palestinians have ever had to do is recognize Israel as a Jewish state and promise to live in peace with it. But when Israel has proposed trading land for peace -- as it did in 2000 when it agreed to give the Palestinians a sovereign state in more than 95% of the West Bank and all of Gaza -- the Palestinian leadership rejected the offer, and instead responded by sending waves of suicide terrorists into Israel. Meanwhile, Palestinian radio, television, and school curricula remain filled with glorification of terrorists, demonization of Jews, and the daily repeated message that Israel should cease to exist. So it‚Äôs not hard to explain the Middle-East dispute. One side wants the other dead. The motto of Hamas, the Palestinian rulers of Gaza, is: ‚ÄúWe love death as much as the Jews love life.‚Äù There are 22 Arab states in the world -- stretching from the Atlantic Ocean to the Indian Ocean. There is one ‚ÄúJewish State‚Äù in the world. And it is about the size of New Jersey. In fact, tiny El Salvador is larger than Israel. Finally, think about these two questions: If, tomorrow, Israel laid down its arms and announced, ‚ÄúWe will fight no more,‚Äù what would happen? And if the Arab countries around Israel laid down their arms and announced ‚ÄúWe will fight no more,‚Äù what would happen? In the first case there would be an immediate destruction of the state of Israel and the mass murder of its Jewish population. In the second case, there would be peace the next day. As I said at the outset, it is a simple problem to describe: one side wants the other dead -- and if it didn‚Äôt, there would be peace. Please remember this: There has never been a state in the geographic area known as Palestine that was not Jewish. Israel is the third Jewish state to exist in that area. There was never an Arab state, never a Palestinian state, never a Muslim or any other state. That‚Äôs the issue: why can‚Äôt the one Jewish state the size of El Salvador be allowed to exist? That is the Middle-East problem. I‚Äôm Dennis Prager."

Today, President Abdel Fattah El-Sisi received the Italian Deputy Prime Minister and Minister of Foreign Affairs and International Cooperation, Antonio Tajani. The meeting was attended by Minister of Foreign Affairs Sameh Shoukry, the Italian ambassador to Egypt and a number of Italian officials. The Spokesman for the Presidency said the meeting confirmed the mutual aspiration to support the distinguished partnership between the two countries, and to continue the positive development and strong momentum for bilateral cooperation, in light of the historical relations between Egypt and Italy and the deep cultural ties between the two peoples. President El-Sisi and Mr.Tajani discussed ways to enhance economic cooperation and increase trade between the two countries. They stressed the importance of strengthening the ongoing work to support food production and joint industrial cooperation, in addition to capitalizing on the opportunities available in the field of energy and renewable energy. They also highlighted growing investments by the Italian companies in Egypt. Regarding the international and regional situation, the meeting touched on the current Palestinian-Israeli developments. Both sides agreed on the gravity of the situation, and the importance of working to stop the escalation and achieve calm between the two sides for the region‚Äôs stability. This is while affirming that a just and comprehensive peace, based on the two-state solution, is of utmost necessity for the stability of the region. Mr.Tajani affirmed Italy‚Äôs reliance on Egypt‚Äôs key and vital role in this regard. President El-Sisi explained that Egypt is exerting efforts and intensifying contacts to contain the situation to prevent its exacerbation, stressing the importance of stopping the bloodshed, protecting civilians, preventing targeting them, and preventing the deterioration of the humanitarian conditions of the Palestinian people, warning of the dangerous security and humanitarian consequences of the ongoing conflict, and the importance of the European and international role in supporting the path of calm and negotiations.

text: Ancient Nubia and the Kingdom of Kush The history of northern Sudan stretches back to an astonishing 300,000 years ago. It was home to one of sub-Saharan Africa's most ancient kingdoms, the renowned Kingdom of Kush (approximately 2500‚Äì1500 BC). This culture was responsible for producing some of the finest pottery found in the Nile Valley, including the exquisite Kerma glasses. Sudan was highly sought after for its abundant natural resources, including gold, ebony, and ivory, which captivated the attention of many, including the ancient Egyptians during the Old Kingdom (about 2686‚Äì2181 BCE). This pursuit of wealth often led to conflict as Egyptian and Sudanese rulers vied for control of trade routes. Around 1700 BC, Kush emerged as the dominant state in the Nile valley. This set the stage for a series of conflicts with Egypt, culminating in the conquest of Kush by Thutmose I (1504‚Äì1492 BC). In the western and southern regions, Neolithic cultures persisted, beyond the reach of Egyptian rule. Egypt eventually withdrew in the 11th century BCE, allowing Sudanese kings to rise in power. They not only invaded Egypt but also ruled as pharaohs (around 747‚Äì656 BCE), at the peak of their reign uniting the Nile valley from Khartoum to the Mediterranean. King Taharqo's sphinx stands as a testament to the authority and influence of the Kushites. Although they were eventually expelled from Egypt by the Assyrians, their kingdom continued to flourish in Sudan for another millennium. The monuments and art from this era are a fascinating blend of Pharaonic, Greco-Roman, and indigenous African traditions. This unique fusion can be observed in relics like the relief of the chapel of Queen Shanakdhakete and the aegis of Isis, both housed in the museum's collection. Around 1070 BC, the Egyptians withdrew from Sudan, and in the 9th century, a second powerful Kushite dynasty emerged. Seizing the opportunity presented by political instability and disunity in Egypt, King Kashta extended his control to Thebes in Egypt by the mid-eighth century BC. His successor Piankhi (Piye) went on to achieve complete dominion over the Egyptian Nile Valley around 716 BC, leaving an indelible mark on the pages of history.

Prime Minister Extends Gratitude to Fiji Airways for Heroic Rescue of Fijians from Israel Amidst Conflict ‚ÄúToday with your safe return, I want to make clear our condemnation of the terrorist attack by Hamas which targeted innocent non-combatants and resulted in continuing loss of life. We also stand with Israel. Israel has the right to defend itself and its people.‚Äù This was the heartfelt message shared by Prime Minister, Sitiveni Rabuka this morning while welcoming 198 Fiji nationals and 48 fellow Pacific and international Pilgrims who had been safely evacuated from Israel. The Prime Minister expressed immense joy and gratitude for their safe return, invoking a sense of blessing and unity within Fiji. He also commended the pilgrims for their unwavering faith and cooperation throughout the process. ‚ÄúToday, I stand with all Fijians to commend the valor, sacrifice, and tireless efforts of all who organised the daring but well-planned and executed repatriation of our fellow citizens and pilgrims possible, amidst the ongoing strife in Israel.‚Äù ‚ÄúI say well planned and executed because this was a Labour of Love.‚Äù The Prime Minister also praised the meticulously planned repatriation mission orchestrated by Fiji Airways amidst the ongoing strife, particularly the pilots, for their courage and world-class expertise in undertaking this historic mission in an uncertain situation. ‚ÄúFiji Airways was able to fly this A330 into the David Ben Gurion International Airport (under the protection of Israel‚Äôs ‚ÄòIron Dome‚Äô) on 10th October with a turnaround time of only 2 hours and whisk our people to safety.‚Äù ‚ÄúThe well-coordinated and targeted mission to rescue our citizens and fellow pilgrims underscores your government's commitment to the well-being of Fijian nationals.‚Äù ‚ÄúWe express our profound gratitude to our diplomatic missions in New York, Canberra, and Abu Dhabi, the international diplomatic community, and our dedicated team here in Fiji. They tirelessly negotiated, made calls, and facilitated all that was needed to bring our people home.‚Äù The Prime Minister stressed a peaceful resolution and de-escalation of the conflict, emphasising Fiji's commitment to pursuing diplomatic, non-violent solutions to conflicts in line with the Pacific's "Zone of Peace" initiative. #peoplescoalition #FijiGovernment #FijiNews

Tali√±o-Mendoza kasama ang mga kinatawan mula sa ahensiya ng nasyunal na pamahalaan, departamento ng kapitolyo, at lokal na pamahalaan ng nasabing bayan upang magbigay ng iba't ibang serbisyo sa mamamayan dito. Sa ilalim ng liderato ni Governor Mendoza isinagawa ang "Serbisyong Totoo Caravan", alinsunod sa programa ng nasyunal na pamahalaan na wakasan ang insurhensiya sa buong bansa sa pamamagitan ng "whole-of-nation approach", na ipinapatupad sa lalawigan sa tulong ng Provincial Task Force to End Local Communist Armed Conflict (NTF-ELCAC). Sa mensahe ng gobernadora, inihayag nito na seryoso ang kanyang pamunuan na ipaabot sa mga Cotabate√±o, kahit na sa malalayong lugar, ang serbisyo ng gobyerno at ipadama ang malasakit ng pamahalaan upang makamit ang pangmatagalang kapayapaan at kaunlaran. Sa katunanayan, naglaan si Gov. Mendoza ng 50 milyong piso para sa pagtaguyod ng ELCAC program sa lalawigan. Ibinahagi rin ng ina ng probinsya ang kasalukuyang pagsisikap nito para sa mga kapatid na katutubo o indigenous peoples (IPs) ng lalawigan kung saan "pilot areas" ang bayan ng Carmen, Banisilan, at Alamada, na mabibigyan ng hanapbuhay sa pamamagitan ng pagtatanim ng kawayan sa 2,000 ektaryang lupain na pag-aari rin ng mga ito. Tinatayang abot sa sampung libong sahod ang tatanggapin ng bawat indibidwal kada buwan. Hinikayat din nito ang mga residente na makiisa sa pamahalaan at maging mata, tenga, at boses ng mamamayan upang masugpo ang katiwalian at maipaabot ang pangangailangan ng taumbayan. Kasama din ng gonernadora si Department of the Interior and Local Government (DILG) Ali B. Abdullah na nagpahayag ng pagsaludo kay Gov. Mendoza sa suporta nito sa naturang adhikain sa pamamagitan ng paglaan ng kaukulang pondo para sa pagsasagawa ng nasabing caravan Ayon kay PD Ali, naging matagumpay ang implementasyon ng ELCAC sa buong lalawigan dahil sa determinisyon ng butihing gobernadora na dalhin ang mga serbisyo ng gobyerno sa komunidad sa pamamagitan ng ST caravan. Mensahe ng paghanga rin ang ipinaabot ni Ginoong Pedro Arnado, dating miyembro ng makakaliwang grupo at ngayon ay bahagi na ng Speakers Bureau ng Armed Forces of the Philippines. Aniya, nakita na nito ang malasakit ng pamahalaan sa mamamayan lalo na sa mga malalayong lugar at maliliit na sektor sa lipunan. Pinasalamatan nito si Gov. Mendoza na ayon sa kanya dahil sa Serbisyong Totoo caravan naihatid ang napakaraming mga serbisyo at mga proyekto sa mga barangay at mga komunidad. Labis din ang saya ng mga lokal na opisyales na pinangunahan nina Mayor Jonathan Mahimpit at Punong Barangay Helen Gasita dahil sa malaking oportunidad na ibinigay sa kanila ng probinsiya upang maging benepisyaryo ng iba't ibang mga programa at proyekto ang mahigit 2,000 na residente rito. Dumalo rin sa nasabing aktibidad sina TESDA Provincial Director Relly A. Leysa, NCIP Provincial Officer Macapantao Manamba, Provincial IPMR at Ex-Officio Boardmember Arsenio Ampalid, PCL President Rene Rubino, MLGOO Lilibeth Layson, 72nd Infantry Batallion Commander LTC Julius Paclibar, PMAJ Jun Napat ng PNP Pres. Roxas, at marami pang mga lokal na opisyales. Today, Abdel Fattah El-Sisi received a phone call from Sultan of Oman, His Majesty Sultan Haitham bin Tariq. The phone call focused on developments in the current escalation between the Palestinians and Israelis, in light of the grave repercussions on security and stability in the region and the escalating humanitarian suffering incurred by civilians as a result of the conflict. The two leaders agreed on the importance of unifying efforts to urge the parties to calm down and reduce violence. They also reviewed contacts underway in this regard. President El-Sisi and His Majesty the Sultan of Oman underscored the importance of advancing efforts aimed at reaching a just, comprehensive and durable solution to the Palestinian issue, based on the two-state solution, in accordance with the references and resolutions of international legitimacy, and in a manner that achieves security and stability for all peoples in the region.

text: A new blog is up on my site! I thought I‚Äôd share some ways to celebrate a most potent day of magic in the witch‚Äôs calendar, Friday the 13th, and dive a little into the 13 expressions/archetypes of the Great Goddess. Friday is Freya‚Äôs Day, the Norse Goddess of love, lust, beauty, fertility, abundance and war. Freya wages battle on behalf of the oppressed, a warrior in service to others, standing up to injustice. She assists women in labor and those seeking love. She is a death doula, comforting the dying on their transition and transformation. Freya rides a chariot pulled by two black cats ‚Äì a gift from the God of Thunder, Thor. After serving Freya for seven years, the cats were transformed into witches‚Ä¶ disguised as cats; and so, the association between witches and black cats. Work with Freya on your altar with tiger‚Äôs eye, honey or mead, precious metals and in meditation as your guide through personal obstacles or grief, collective conflict, and on the search for community and love. Friday the 13th is the Day of the Goddess ‚Äì the Divine Feminine in her many archetypes. But more on that part later. The number 13 has always been sacred to the Divine Feminine, and those who followed the Lunar calendar and the cycles of Great Cosmic Mother, observed 13 lunar cycles in a year. The solar calendar observes 12 lunar cycles, with a 13th cycle roughly every two and a half years. *Read the rest here: https://monikacarless.com/blog/

Ilustre, Pres. Roxas ang pagbisita ni Gov. Emmylou "Lala" J. Tali√±o-Mendoza kasama ang mga kinatawan mula sa ahensiya ng nasyunal na pamahalaan, departamento ng kapitolyo, at lokal na pamahalaan ng nasabing bayan upang magbigay ng iba't ibang serbisyo sa mamamayan dito. Sa ilalim ng liderato ni Governor Mendoza isinagawa ang "Serbisyong Totoo Caravan", alinsunod sa programa ng nasyunal na pamahalaan na wakasan ang insurhensiya sa buong bansa sa pamamagitan ng "whole-of-nation approach", na ipinapatupad sa lalawigan sa tulong ng Provincial Task Force to End Local Communist Armed Conflict (NTF-ELCAC). Sa mensahe ng gobernadora, inihayag nito na seryoso ang kanyang pamunuan na ipaabot sa mga Cotabate√±o, kahit na sa malalayong lugar, ang serbisyo ng gobyerno at ipadama ang malasakit ng pamahalaan upang makamit ang pangmatagalang kapayapaan at kaunlaran. Sa katunanayan, naglaan si Gov. Mendoza ng 50 milyong piso para sa pagtaguyod ng ELCAC program sa lalawigan. Ibinahagi rin ng ina ng probinsya ang kasalukuyang pagsisikap nito para sa mga kapatid na katutubo o indigenous peoples (IPs) ng lalawigan kung saan "pilot areas" ang bayan ng Carmen, Banisilan, at Alamada, na mabibigyan ng hanapbuhay sa pamamagitan ng pagtatanim ng kawayan sa 2,000 ektaryang lupain na pag-aari rin ng mga ito. Tinatayang abot sa sampung libong sahod ang tatanggapin ng bawat indibidwal kada buwan. Hinikayat din nito ang mga residente na makiisa sa pamahalaan at maging mata, tenga, at boses ng mamamayan upang masugpo ang katiwalian at maipaabot ang pangangailangan ng taumbayan. Kasama din ng gonernadora si Department of the Interior and Local Government (DILG) Ali B. Abdullah na nagpahayag ng pagsaludo kay Gov. Mendoza sa suporta nito sa naturang adhikain sa pamamagitan ng paglaan ng kaukulang pondo para sa pagsasagawa ng nasabing caravan Ayon kay PD Ali, naging matagumpay ang implementasyon ng ELCAC sa buong lalawigan dahil sa determinisyon ng butihing gobernadora na dalhin ang mga serbisyo ng gobyerno sa komunidad sa pamamagitan ng ST caravan. Mensahe ng paghanga rin ang ipinaabot ni Ginoong Pedro Arnado, dating miyembro ng makakaliwang grupo at ngayon ay bahagi na ng Speakers Bureau ng Armed Forces of the Philippines. Aniya, nakita na nito ang malasakit ng pamahalaan sa mamamayan lalo na sa mga malalayong lugar at maliliit na sektor sa lipunan. Pinasalamatan nito si Gov. Mendoza na ayon sa kanya dahil sa Serbisyong Totoo caravan naihatid ang napakaraming mga serbisyo at mga proyekto sa mga barangay at mga komunidad. Labis din ang saya ng mga lokal na opisyales na pinangunahan nina Mayor Jonathan Mahimpit at Punong Barangay Helen Gasita dahil sa malaking oportunidad na ibinigay sa kanila ng probinsiya upang maging benepisyaryo ng iba't ibang mga programa at proyekto ang mahigit 2,000 na residente rito. Dumalo rin sa nasabing aktibidad sina TESDA Provincial Director Relly A. Leysa, NCIP Provincial Officer Macapantao Manamba, Provincial IPMR at Ex-Officio Boardmember Arsenio Ampalid, PCL President Rene Rubino, MLGOO Lilibeth Layson, 72nd Infantry Batallion Commander LTC Julius Paclibar, PMAJ Jun Napat ng PNP Pres. Roxas, at marami pang mga lokal na opisyales. Nakisaya rin sa aktibidad ang ipinagmamalaki ng mga Roxasanon at Cotabate√±o na si "Tawag ng Tanghalan" Mindanao Contender Eva Mae Alpuerto na nag-alay ng awitin sa mga kababayan nito.//idcd-pgo-gonzales/photoby:SMNanini, lqgonzales//

A CALL TO PRAYER. Praying for peace in times of war can feel like facing a dragon with a paper sword. But we know that is only an illusion. War is not all-powerful, inevitable or unstoppable. Its origins are in the same place as peace: in the human heart. When we pray for peace, we pray to reach the hearts of other human beings, on all sides of the conflict, to restore a sense of compassion and hope. We seek to pour the water of life onto the flames of hate, one person at a time, until the rage subsides. So please, keep praying with me for peace, no matter how tempted you may be to despair. Confront the dragon with your love, as you work in every way you can, for the cause of peace.

It has been gut wrenching to read about the unprecedented terrorist attacks on the Israeli people. Children decapitated in their beds, 240 young people slaughtered at a music festival for peace, little ones kidnapped and held hostage. My heart breaks for the loss of these precious lives and the fear and unspeakable pain our Jewish brothers and sisters are feeling. It has also been wild to read the justifications, the rationalizations and outright, vile anti-Semitic hate spewed at Israelis during this dark hour. Not just from bots on social media but from Influencers, media groups, celebrities, Harvard student associations, Christian conservatives and more. This is Israel‚Äôs 9/11 - even worse - and yet many have chosen this very moment to publicly side with their killers and downplay their pain. A BLM chapter has even posted an image of a terrorist paraglider with their support for Hamas ‚Äúfreedom fighters.‚Äù Hamas terrorists used paragliders to land in Israeli villages and shoot to death men, women and children. It is all shameful and sick. Denouncing Hamas does not mean you do not have great empathy for the many innocents in Gaza, caught up in this war. My heart also breaks for children caught in cross fire and families terrified as they face rockets, intended for their leaders. Hamas is evil and does not value their precious lives, either. Pray for justice and peace. For the protection of *all* civilians, Israeli and Palestinian, for an end to Hamas and all terrorist overlords, and for a future of flourishing and peace for Israel and the people of Palestine. I just filmed a podcast episode on the events of the weekend and exploring and exposing the narratives, questions, and disagreements on the Israeli/Palestinian conflict.

Marcos, Jr., DSWD Secretary Rex Gatchalian at kay DSWD XII Regional Director Loreto V. Tali√±o-Mendoza sa patuloy na pagbuhos ng biyaya sa pamamagitan ng iba't ibang programa at proyekto mula sa pamahalaang panlalawigan at maging sa iba pang mga ahensya ng gobyerno. Ang SLP ay isang ‚Äúcapacity-building program‚Äù na may layuning suportahan at palakasin ang programang kapayapaan at kaunlaran sa pamamagitan ng pagbibigay ng proyektong pangkabuhayan at pataasin ang partisipasyon ng mga mamayan sa mga conflict-affected communities sa pagpapaunlad ng kanilang komunidad. 255 Fijians Embark on Historic Repatriation Journey 11 October, 2023 - With a sense of gratitude, Prime Minister Sitiveni Rabuka is relieved that a chartered Fiji Airways flight that departed from Ben Gurion Airport earlier today, is successfully bringing 255 Fijians back to their homeland. Among the passengers were Fiji's AICAT (Agricultural Institutes of the Center for Agricultural Technology) students who were pursuing studies in agriculture in Israel, the 200 Fijians who had journeyed to Jerusalem to partake in the Feast of Tabernacles as well as a group of Pacific Islanders. Prime Minister Rabuka extends his sincere appreciation to all parties involved in making this mission a success. ‚ÄúIn these trying times, it is important to express our sympathy for all those affected by the recent conflict between Israel and Hamas. Our thoughts are with the people of the region, and we hope for a swift and lasting resolution that brings peace and stability to all,‚Äù Prime Minister Rabuka said. The Prime Minister acknowledges the tireless efforts of the Fiji Airways crew and Incident Team who worked diligently to navigate the complex risks and options associated with planning this crucial flight. ‚ÄúTheir dedication and expertise have made this mission possible and have reunited our citizens with their families and loved ones. This mission is a historic one for the Fijian Government, as it represents our very first rescue operation.‚Äù ‚ÄúThe successful repatriation of our citizens is a testament to the commitment and determination of our nation to safeguard the well-being of all Fijians, no matter where they are in the world.‚Äù The Prime Minister also extended his gratitude to the Ministry of Foreign Affairs for their coordination and arrangements with our international allies. ‚ÄúThis collaboration and support from our friends and partners have been instrumental in ensuring the safe return of our citizens.‚Äù The Prime Minister would also like to express his heartfelt thanks to all those who offered their prayers, well-wishes, and support during this mission. ‚ÄúThe collective strength of our nation in times of need is a source of great pride and unity. The safe return of these Fijians is a testament to the resilience of our nation, and the Fijian spirit that binds us together. We will continue to work diligently to ensure the well-being and safety of all Fijians, both at home and abroad.‚Äù PC: Kelepi Abariga

Today, President Abdel Fattah El-Sisi received a phone call from Prime Minister of the Netherlands, Mark Rutte. The President and the Dutch Prime Minister discussed the ongoing developments in the Gaza Strip and the dangerous escalation between the Palestinians and Israelis over the past days. The two sides agreed on the gravity of the current conflict, given its formidable humanitarian consequences as well as its security and political repercussions that will extend to the entire region. President El-Sisi reiterated that Egypt is continuing its endeavors to advance coordinated regional and international efforts to urge all parties to adopt the path of calm and de-escalation and reduce military operations. He emphasized that settling the Palestinian issue through just and lasting peace is the way to achieving security and stability in the region.

The Mole: Bulldogs meeting to decide Josh Addo-Carr's future after 'dramatic' week Josh Addo-Carr will sit down with Bulldogs officials on Friday in a meeting that could have dramatic implications for the star winger's future. Rumours are swirling throughout the game that 'The Foxx' wants out of Belmore after a dramatic week in which he was suspended from the Australian team and forced to apologise for a social media post concerning the crisis in the Middle East. Addo-Carr and his management will meet with Bulldogs football boss Phil Gould to sort out where the tryscoring ace stands. Sources close to Addo-Carr say he isn't happy with the level of support given to him after he was suspended for two matches after video emerged of him punching a man during the Koori Knockout. The Bulldogs, for their part, are said to be unhappy with Addo-Carr's behaviour at the Knockout and his social media post on the Israel-Palestine conflict. The star winger put a photo on Instagram of the Palestinian and Aboriginal flags with the caption "One struggle, one fight". The following day he did a backflip - no doubt at the request of Bulldogs and NRL officials, stating he wanted to apologise "for any offence I have caused due to my recent social media post". "As a proud First Nations man, I saw a message of support against displacement and land rights, and I shared this without full consideration to, or understanding of, the current events happening overseas," he added. On the field, The Foxx has been a success in his two seasons at Canterbury after five years in Melbourne. In a struggling side, he still managed to score 16 tries last year and 11 tries in 2023. But he came to the club on big dollars and the Bulldogs would be able to use that money on players closer to the middle of the park if he left with two years remaining on his contract. Several rival NRL clubs are certain to be interested in the speedy winger - if he cannot resolve his issues with the Bulldogs on Friday.

Special Intention :

Let us offer our prayer today for peace in Israel - Gaza conflict, and prayers to all victims of war, to those who died, may their souls rest in peace. üôèüèª

‚úùÔ∏èIn the name of the Father, and of the Son, and of the Holy Spirit. Amen.

‚úùÔ∏èSay the Apostles Creed: I believe in God, the Father Almighty, Creator of heaven and earth; and in Jesus Christ his only Son, Our Lord; Who was conceived by the Holy Ghost, born of the Virgin Mary, suffered under Pontius Pilate, was crucified, died, and was buried. He descended into hell; the third day He arose again from the dead; He ascended into heaven, sitteth at the right hand of God the Father Almighty; from thence He shall come to judge the living and the dead. I believe in the Holy Ghost, the holy Catholic Church, the communion of Saints, the forgiveness of sins, the resurrection of the body, and life everlasting. Amen.

‚úùÔ∏èOne Our Father, three Hail Marys, one Glory Be to the Father.

·É¶œ†‚Ç°·É¶¬∏.‚úª¬¥¬¥¬Ø`‚úª.¬∏¬∏
‚úùÔ∏èThe First Glorious Mystery - The Resurrection of Jesus. If the Spirit of God, who raised Jesus from death, lives in you, then he who raised Christ from death will also give life to your mortal bodies by the presence of his Spirit in you. (Romans 8:11).

On Sunday morning the women came to the tomb to embalm the body of our Lord. While on the way, they looked and were astonished that the stone had been rolled away. It seemed that Jesus Christ had lost the battle. But the fact is that He won! Jesus conquered the darkest realities of sin and death by the power of His resurrection. 

The Glory Realized. Jesus, your victory over sin and death is real. Yet this world seems so caught up in tragedies which give the illusion that darkness is winning. Increase our faith so that we can know that the victory is ours. Through the Eucharist, Your Word, and the Church, help us to grow in Your love. 

One Our Father, Ten Hail Marys, One Glory Be, the Fatima Prayer
FRUIT OF THE MYSTERY: Faith 

·É¶œ†‚Ç°·É¶¬∏.‚úª¬¥¬¥¬Ø`‚úª.¬∏¬∏
‚úùÔ∏èThe Second Glorious Mystery - The Ascension of Jesus. As he was blessing them, he departed from them and was taken up into heaven. (Luke 24:51). Jesus ascended to the right hand of the Father. He promised us that we would not be alone and that He would be with us all days, even to the end of time. Jesus goes to the Father to intercede for us and to prepare a place for us.

We Can Do All Things. Jesus, You promised that Your power would work in us if we believe. "You will do greater things than these because I go to the Father." It is precisely because You are at the right hand of the Father that we experience Your presence and power in our lives.

One Our Father, Ten Hail Marys, One Glory Be, the Fatima Prayer
FRUIT OF THE MYSTERY: Hope

·É¶œ†‚Ç°·É¶¬∏.‚úª¬¥¬¥¬Ø`‚úª.¬∏¬∏
‚úùÔ∏èThe Third Glorious Mystery - The Gift of the Holy Spirit. When the day of Pentecost came, all the believers were gathered together in one place. Suddenly there was a noise from the sky that sounded like a strong wind blowing, and it filled the whole house. (Acts 2:1-2).

The disciples were gathered together in prayer and the Blessed Mother was in their midst. All of a sudden the Holy Spirit came in the form of fire upon all those gathered in prayer. People from different countries and backgrounds were all united by the power of the Holy Spirit.

Inner Strength. Lord Jesus, You were able to transform Peter. The one who denied you could now stand tall. Send forth Your Holy Spirit upon the Church so that we, too, may be restored and renewed. Let Your Spirit fill our hearts with praise and adoration. Make us bold in proclaiming the trust of our faith in You. 

One Our Father, Ten Hail Marys, One Glory Be, the Fatima Prayer
FRUIT OF THE MYSTERY: Love of God

·É¶œ†‚Ç°·É¶¬∏.‚úª¬¥¬¥¬Ø`‚úª.¬∏¬∏
‚úùÔ∏èThe Fourth Glorious Mystery - The Assumption of Mary. She was given the two wings of a large eagle, in order to fly to her place in the desert, where she will be taken care of . . . safe from the dragon's attack. (Revelation 12:14). 

Being raised to heaven, body and soul. Mary is at the right hand of Jesus. Jesus is at the right hand of the Father. Mary is in an unique place to intercede for us. She is in union with the Blessed Trinity by the grace of God.

Future Dignity. Mary, the gift that you received was a gift for the Church. It brings us hope and comfort to know that God is providing for our eternal life. Mary, help us not to focus on passing pleasures, but rather to set our hearts on the will of the Father! 

One Our Father, Ten Hail Marys, One Glory Be, the Fatima Prayer

255 Fijians Embark on Historic Repatriation Journey 11 October, 2023 - With a sense of gratitude, Prime Minister Sitiveni Rabuka is relieved that a chartered Fiji Airways flight that departed from Ben Gurion Airport earlier today, is successfully bringing 255 Fijians back to their homeland. Among the passengers were Fiji's AICAT (Agricultural Institutes of the Center for Agricultural Technology) students who were pursuing studies in agriculture in Israel, the 200 Fijians who had journeyed to Jerusalem to partake in the Feast of Tabernacles as well as a group of Pacific Islanders. Prime Minister Rabuka extends his sincere appreciation to all parties involved in making this mission a success. ‚ÄúIn these trying times, it is important to express our sympathy for all those affected by the recent conflict between Israel and Hamas. Our thoughts are with the people of the region, and we hope for a swift and lasting resolution that brings peace and stability to all,‚Äù Prime Minister Rabuka said. The Prime Minister acknowledges the tireless efforts of the Fiji Airways crew and Incident Team who worked diligently to navigate the complex risks and options associated with planning this crucial flight. ‚ÄúTheir dedication and expertise have made this mission possible and have reunited our citizens with their families and loved ones. This mission is a historic one for the Fijian Government, as it represents our very first rescue operation.‚Äù ‚ÄúThe successful repatriation of our citizens is a testament to the commitment and determination of our nation to safeguard the well-being of all Fijians, no matter where they are in the world.‚Äù The Prime Minister also extended his gratitude to the Ministry of Foreign Affairs for their coordination and arrangements with our international allies. ‚ÄúThis collaboration and support from our friends and partners have been instrumental in ensuring the safe return of our citizens.‚Äù The Prime Minister would also like to express his heartfelt thanks to all those who offered their prayers, well-wishes, and support during this mission. ‚ÄúThe collective strength of our nation in times of need is a source of great pride and unity. The safe return of these Fijians is a testament to the resilience of our nation, and the Fijian spirit that binds us together. We will continue to work diligently to ensure the well-being and safety of all Fijians, both at home and abroad.‚Äù PC: Kelepi Abariga

I am opposed to plans for a blanket ban on Palestinian Australians gathering in NSW in support of their people. The civilian suffering in the conflict is universal, and we should not have the right to deny Australians the ability to peacefully assemble. Leaders within the Palestinian community, including religious institutions, need to come out strongly to rebuke calls for violence and condemn the slaughter of innocent civilians by Hamas. The government and police need to work with organizers to prevent the celebration of terrorism against civilians and take direct action against any incitement to violence. Any display of support for terrorism must be dealt with swiftly. If organizers are unable to do this and are not confident that their presence may not further inflame the situation, they should take matters into their own hands to minimize the damage this will do to their cause publicly in Australia. It is their responsibility, and the rest of the country has every right to judge their actions on the day. If the ban stays in place and a protest led by the same organizers goes ahead and we see the same scenes as the other night in front of the Opera House but this time with clashes with police, the damage to the perception of Palestinian people in Australia will be immense. Australians should always have every right to oppose war and advocate for peace. At times like this, it can be uncomfortable to be principled, but that is what sets us apart from much of the turmoil around the world.

People ask me all the time if I am "pro-Israel" because I am a Jew who has lived in Israel, and my answer is that being "pro-Israel" or being "pro-Palestine" or being a "Zionist" does not properly capture the nuance of thought most people do or should have about this issue. It certainly doesn't capture mine. I have a lot to say. I‚Äôve spent the last 72 hours writing, texting, and talking to Israelis, Jews, Muslims, and Palestinians. Much of my reaction is going to piss off people on "both sides," but I am exhausted and hurting and I do not think there is any way to discuss this situation without being radically honest about my views. So I'm going to try to say what I believe to be true the best I can. Let me start with this: It could have been me. That's a hard thought to shake when watching the videos out of Israel ‚Äî the concert goers fleeing across an empty expanse, the hostages being paraded through the streets, the people shot in the head at bus stops or in their cars. I went to those parties in the desert, I rubbed shoulders with Israelis and Arabs and Jews and Muslims, I could have easily accepted an invitation to some concert near Sderot and gone without a care, only to be indiscriminately slaughtered. Or, perhaps worse, taken hostage and tortured. I don‚Äôt believe Hamas is killing Israelis to liberate themselves, nor do I believe they are doing it to make peace. They're doing this because they represent the devil on the shoulder of every oppressed Palestinian who has lost someone in this conflict. They're doing it because they want vengeance. They are evening the score, and acting on the worst of our human impulses, to respond to blood with blood ‚Äî an inclination that is easy to give in to after what their people have endured. It should not be hard to understand their logic ‚Äî it is only hard to accept that humans are capable of being driven to this. Not defending Hamas is a very low bar to clear. Please clear it. It‚Äôs not possible to recap the entire 5,000 year history of people fighting over this strip of land in one newsletter. There are plenty of easily accessible places you can learn about it if you want to (and, by the way, many of you should ‚Äî far too many people speak on this issue with an obscene amount of ignorance, loads of arrogance, and a narrow historical lens focused on the last few decades). But I'll briefly highlight a few things that are important to me. In my opinion, the Jewish people have a legitimate historical claim to the land of Israel. Jews had already been expelled and returned and expelled again a half dozen times before the rise of the Muslim and Arab rule of the Ottoman Empire. Of course it‚Äôs messy because we Jews and Arabs and Muslims are all cousins and descendents of the same Canaanites. But Arabs won the land centuries ago the same way Israel and Jews won it in the 20th century: Through conflict and war. The British defeated the Ottoman Empire and then came the Balfour Declaration, which amounted to the British granting the area to the Jewish people, a promise they‚Äôd later try to renege on ‚Äî all before the wars that have defined the region since 1948. That historical moment in the late 1940s was unique. After World War II, with many Arab and Muslim states already in existence, and after six million Jews were slaughtered, the global community felt it was important to grant the Jewish people a homeland. In a more logical or just world that homeland would have been in Europe as a kind of reparation for what the Nazis and others before them had done to the Jews, or perhaps in the Americas ‚Äî like Alaska ‚Äî or somewhere else. But the Jews wanted Israel, the British had taken to the Zionist movement, the British had conquered the Ottoman Empire which handed them control of the land, and America and Europe didn‚Äôt want the Jews. As a result, we got Israel. The Arab states had already rejected a partitioned Israel repeatedly before World War II and rejected it again after the Holocaust and the end of the war. They did not want to give up even a little bit of their land to a bunch of Jewish interlopers who were granted it all of a sudden by British interlopers who had arrived a hundred years prior. Who could blame them? It had been centuries since Jews lived there in large numbers, and now they wanted to return in waves as secularized Europeans. Many of us would probably react the same way. So, just as humans have done forever, they fought. The many existing Arab states turned against the burgeoning new Jewish state. One side won and one side lost. This is the brutal and broken and violent world we live in, but it is what created the global world order we have now. Are Israelis and British people "colonizers" because of this 20th century history? Sure. But that view flattens thousands of years of history and conflict, and the context of World War I and World War II. Comptroller Oramalugo Strengthens Ties with Local Community In a display of mutual respect and collaboration, Customs Area Controller, Oyo/Osun Command, Comptroller Ben Oramalugo, embarked on a courtesy visit to his Imperial Majesty, Oba Mohood Olalekan Ishola Balogun, a gesture geared towards strengthening ties with Local Monarchy. According to a press statement released on Tuesday 10th, October, 2023, by the Public Relations Officer Superintendent of Customs Kayode Wey, Comptroller Oramalugo emphasized the Nigeria Customs Service's commitment to maintaining a transparent and efficient import and export system, which directly impacts the economic well-being of the region. He also highlighted the role of the Service in curbing illegal activities such as smuggling, illicit trade, which can disrupt the local economy and threaten security. "The core mandates of the Nigeria Customs Service include Trade Facilitation, Revenue Generation and Suppression of Smuggling. These values I assured His Imperial Majesty to uphold while performing my duties,‚Äù he stated. The Customs Area Controller conveyed his gratitude for the warm reception by Oba Mohood Olalekan Ishola Balogun and his council. He assured the monarch that the Nigeria Customs Service is dedicated to collaborating closely with the local communities to ensure the prosperity and welfare of the region. He solicited further cooperation and a peaceful working environment for his Officers to perform their duties, adding that it would eliminate any form of conflict between citizens of the State and Officers and Men of the service working within the state. Responding, His Imperial Majesty, the Olubadan of Ibadan Land, assured the Area Controller of further cooperation with the Command and Service in general while highlighting the already existing relationship between the Palace and the Customs Command.

BCS175/150 world tour update. The situation with the 175 and MTU is getting complicated causing extreme uncertainty and unknowns to the world tour schedule. As of today, we have decided to deploy the workhorse BCS150 back into the world tour schedule. She has about 5 weeks of work to be ready, as well as the L&H 33 that was beat up pretty bad earlier this year in Brazil, lots of damage from running her hard. Actually we ran that 33 2600nm miles on plane in 15-25 knot seas, not counting the trolling miles. Even the tower legs are cracked and need welding. She will be made to be better than before and with her Simrad SY50 sonar tuned up, plus installing a Starlink so we may broadcast live from Ascensions to you devoted and crazy followers. Will do the South Atlantic run Jan to April on the 150/33, then reevaluate based on the status of the 175 at that time. Given the conflict with Israel, the option of the 175 heading to the Suez Canal to the Indian Ocean is no longer possible. We‚Äôll focus on South Atlantic with the 150/33 January to April, worry about the rest of the year later. Buy Advil stocks as we‚Äôll be consuming plenty as Old Company runs around on a 33 footer again. Can‚Äôt wait!!! As for the detailed information on MTU and Damen, I am still not prepared to share the details yet. It‚Äôs getting messy instead of clarity.

I‚Äôm tired. Give out. Not just from the day, but from the battle. I‚Äôm weary. It would be easy not to take a stand, but I can‚Äôt live with myself if I do that. Let me explain what has worn me down. And I do this to tell you that you, too, must be strong. yesterday I made clear that onion rings can never be ordered as a substitute for french fries. That is never a choice. Onion rings can only be in addition to french fries. You can choose not to order french fries and get nothing, but you can‚Äôt choose between those two. if you‚Äôve ordered french fries and you want onion rings in addition, I salute you. I understand. If you‚Äôre with your wife or a friend or your kids and you‚Äôve ordered meals that come with fries and you order an onion ring to share, you were raised right. I knew when I said this that I was picking a scab for the wound of American society. I guess I did not expect big onion ring to come after me. An army of onion ring minions has been attacking me by emails. Mercilessly. Repeatedly. And onslaught of the onion ring army. they don‚Äôt seem to understand the rules. I can only assume they were not raised right. They are bringing this battle to my doorstep. And I will fight them until the death. Because it is the right thing to do. Never avoid conflict.  in this case it would simply be kicking the can down the road until they bolster their resources and come at you later. No matter the cost, no matter how high the Burden I must bear, this is a fight I cannot avoid, and I will win it. be strong.

Kinumpirma ni Department of Foreign Affairs Sec. Enrique Manalo na dalawang Pinoy ang nasawi sa gulo sa Israel. Hours after the Fiji Airways flight, carrying more than 200 passengers, including Fijians, departed from Ben Gurion Airport in Tel Aviv, Israel, reports emerged that Hamas‚Äô Al-Qassam had fired multiple rockets toward the airport. We also wholly reject the violations to which the country's male and female citizens are exposed, their exposure to killing, forced displacement, and their loss of their livelihoods, their money, and everything they possess, without any right or consideration given to them by both sides of the conflict. Weapons do not bring peace, and wars do not lead to safety. Most wars ended with peace agreements but with heavy loss of life and complete destruction of the economy in the country. Sudan and its citizens have reached their worst since the beginning of this war. Therefore, this war must stop immediately. Strength does not lie in those who win the war, but weakness is always in those who lose peace. To the honourable People's Armed Forces in our national institutions, know well that our position on this accursed war is not against you, but it is against your leaders and against everyone who harms the soil and citizens of this country and whom we know very well does not care about the peace of this country and the safety of its people. Artifact: Clay prism Provenience: Nineveh iraq Period: Neo-Assyrian (ca. 911-612 BC) Current location: British Museum London Text genre language Royal inscription Akkadian The Taylor Prism is a large (38.5 cm high) six-sided clay document which contains the annals of Sennacherib, written down in 691 BC. The prism was discovered in the ruins of the armoury in Nineveh, where it would likely have been deposited in the foundations. The artifact was acquired by the British Consul in Baghdad Col. R. Taylor in 1830 and subsequently donated to the British Museum, where it has remained. As one of the earliest, longest cuneiform texts to be discovered it played a significant role in deciphering and understanding Akkadian cuneiform. The document is most celebrated outside of assyriology for its account of the siege of Jerusalem in 701 BC. King Hezekiah of Judah is said to have been locked up like a bird in a cage in Jerusalem his royal city The account details the destruction 46 towns in Judah the payment of a heavy tribute by Sennacherib, and the deportation of 200,150 people This was one of the first cuneiform texts discovered to provide historians with a welcome opportunity to examine stories from both sides of an ancient military conflict

15 lessons from Emotional Intelligence: Why It Can Matter More Than IQ by Daniel Goleman: 1. Emotional intelligence (EI) is the ability to understand and manage your own emotions, as well as the emotions of others. 2. EI is just as important for success in life as IQ, and perhaps even more so. 3. EI consists of five key skills: self-awareness, self-regulation, motivation, empathy, and social skills. 4. Self-awareness is the ability to recognize and understand your own emotions. 5. Self-regulation is the ability to manage your emotions and impulses. 6. Motivation is the ability to set and achieve goals. 7. Empathy is the ability to understand and share the feelings of others. 8. Social skills are the ability to build and maintain relationships. 9. EI can be learned and improved over time. 10. EI can help you succeed in all areas of your life, including your personal relationships, your career, and your health. 11. EI can help you make better decisions. When you are aware of your own emotions and the emotions of others, you are better able to weigh all of the factors involved in a decision. 12. EI can help you resolve conflict more effectively. When you can understand and empathize with the other person's perspective, you are more likely to find a solution that works for everyone. 13. EI can help you build stronger relationships. When you are able to communicate your own emotions clearly and understand the emotions of others, you are more likely to build trust and intimacy. 14. EI can help you manage stress and anxiety. When you are able to identify and manage your own emotions, you are better able to cope with stressful situations. 15. EI can lead to better physical health. Studies have shown that people with high EI are less likely to suffer from heart disease, stroke, and other chronic health conditions. How to improve your emotional intelligence: ‚Ä¢ Pay attention to your emotions. Notice how you feel throughout the day and try to identify the triggers that cause your emotions to change. ‚Ä¢ Label your emotions. Once you can identify your emotions, put a name to them. This will help you to better understand what you are feeling and why. ‚Ä¢ Manage your emotions. Once you understand your emotions, you can develop strategies for managing them in a healthy way. For example, if you are feeling angry, you might try taking a few deep breaths or going for a walk. ‚Ä¢ Empathize with others. Try to put yourself in the shoes of others and see things from their perspective. This will help you to better understand their feelings and motivations. ‚Ä¢ Develop your social skills. Practice communicating effectively, building relationships, and resolving conflict. There are many resources available to help you improve your emotional intelligence. You can find books, articles, and even online courses on the topic. You can also work with a therapist or coach to develop your EI skills. Financial sector stability is a prerequisite for sustainable growth and inclusion. Strengthening financial stability frameworks can be challenging in low-income or fragile and conflict affected states, where human resources are scarce and initial capacity is low. In such cases, it is essential to prioritize and sequence capacity building over a longer time and provide hands-on expert support. The Financial Sector Stability Review (FSSR) proposes a well-structured approach to designing financial sector reforms based on a thorough diagnostic of capacity gaps. FSSR recipient countries benefit from a well-prioritized package of technical assistance, in many cases supported by resident technical advisors, who work in close partnership with the authorities. This event will present how the IMF, with donor support through the Financial Sector Stability Fund, has helped the authorities from The Gambia and Sierra Leone catalyze reforms in their financial stability frameworks.

Suzanne Fabry (Belgian painter) 1904 - 1985
Autoportrait, 1932
oil on canvas
111 x 74 cm. (43.75 x 29.13 in.)
signed Suzanne Fabry and dated 1932 (lower right)
private collection
¬© photo Sotheby's

Catalogue Note Sotheby's
Upon the advent of the First World War and the subsequent invasion of Belgium by German forces, a young Suzanne Fabry was forced to flee to England along with her father, the renowned Symbolist painter √âmile Fabry. Having spent time in Herefordshire and St Ives, the family returned to Brussels at the end of the conflict, where Fabry‚Äôs upbringing continued to be influenced by the political turmoil and ideological upheaval that defined the earlier part of the twentieth century.

Later deciding to become an artist herself, Autoportrait was painted in 1932, in the years following Fabry‚Äôs graduation from the Acad√©mie Royale des Beaux-Arts. A relatively early work by Fabry, this monumental self-portrait nevertheless depicts an artist who is fully confident in her skills and assured of her own sense of artistic identity. Influenced by her father‚Äôs symbolist tendencies, Fabry was never overshadowed by his legacy. Using her own distinctive style, she went on to create an enigmatic body of work which was dominated by assured yet dream-like portraiture and subtle interrogations of the female form in the post-war environment.

This current work recalls classical depictions of female beauty, whilst also calling them in to question. The slight contortion of Fabry‚Äôs limbs suggests a certain artifice to the pose, whilst her direct gaze and the prominent positioning of her brush reinforce a sense of authority that pre-emptively rejects any attempt to perceive the sitter as a mere aesthetic object. The stripped-back composition further emphasises the sitter‚Äôs commanding presence, whilst also drawing focus to the intricacies of her clothing, this delicate rendering of fabric recalling Fabry‚Äôs later prolific output as costume designer for the Belgian national opera house, La Monnaie. Taking the dual role of artist and muse, Fabry creates a self-portrait that examines the viewer as much as they examine the work itself, and it is through such confrontations that Fabry‚Äôs inimitable skill as a portraitist truly shines.

* * *

Born in Brussels in 1904, Suzanne Fabry was the daughter of the Belgian symbolist painter √âmile Fabry (1865‚Äì1966) and his wife Virginie Duch√™nes. Her brother, Barth√©l√©my, was born in 1898. Three years before Suzanne‚Äôs birth, her father was named Professor of Drawing at the l‚ÄôAcad√©mie Royale des Beaux-Arts de Bruxelles, where he had been a student in the 1880s, and her childhood was spent in his house-studio at rue Verte (today rue du Coll√®ge Saint-Michel, n¬∞6) in Woluwe-Saint-Pierre, a south-eastern neighbourhood of Brussels of recent urbanisation. 

At the start of the First World War, √âmile Fabry moved with his family to England, first staying in Herefordshire and later in the Cornish town of Saint-Ives, where he would continue to paint, and they would remain until the end of the conflict. Back in Brussels, the family returned to their home on rue Verte, and in 1923 Suzanne enrolled as a student at the Acad√©mie Royale des Beaux-Arts, where her teachers included Jean Delville (1867-1953) and Constant Montald (1862-1944), two of the founders, alongside Suzanne‚Äôs father, of the group ‚ÄúL'art monumental‚Äù. Their aim was to produce art for the public sphere, monumental in scale and steeped within the cultural tradition of the period, intended to elevate the public conscience by means of representing idealised, universal themes. Their commanding nudes would constitute an important source of inspiration for Suzanne‚Äôs own work. 

Having graduated from the Acad√©mie in 1928, Suzanne began her career as a painter in the 1930s, taking part in the triennial Salon in Antwerp (1930) and the quadrennial Salon in Li√®ge (1931). Around the same time, her father was completing a cycle of large-scale paintings for the entrance and staircase of Brussels‚Äô opera house, La Monnaie, where, many years later, Suzanne and her husband Edmond Delescluze (1905-1993) would be employed as costume and set designer respectively, a collaboration that began in 1948 and is recorded in over 900 sketches and stage maquettes preserved today in the archives of La Monnaie. She continued to pursue her career as a painter, alongside her work as head of the opera‚Äôs costume workshop, until her death in 1985.

Source: Ambrose Naumann Fine Art

EI can be learned and improved over time. 10. EI can help you succeed in all areas of your life, including your personal relationships, your career, and your health. 11. EI can help you make better decisions. When you are aware of your own emotions and the emotions of others, you are better able to weigh all of the factors involved in a decision. 12. EI can help you resolve conflict more effectively. When you can understand and empathize with the other person's perspective, you are more likely to find a solution that works for everyone. 13. EI can help you build stronger relationships. When you are able to communicate your own emotions clearly and understand the emotions of others, you are more likely to build trust and intimacy. 14. EI can help you manage stress and anxiety. When you are able to identify and manage your own emotions, you are better able to cope with stressful situations. 15. EI can lead to better physical health. Studies have shown that people with high EI are less likely to suffer from heart disease, stroke, and other chronic health conditions. How to improve your emotional intelligence: ‚Ä¢ Pay attention to your emotions. Notice how you feel throughout the day and try to identify the triggers that cause your emotions to change. ‚Ä¢ Label your emotions. Once you can identify your emotions, put a name to them. This will help you to better understand what you are feeling and why. ‚Ä¢ Manage your emotions. Once you understand your emotions, you can develop strategies for managing them in a healthy way. For example, if you are feeling angry, you might try taking a few deep breaths or going for a walk. ‚Ä¢ Empathize with others. Try to put yourself in the shoes of others and see things from their perspective. This will help you to better understand their feelings and motivations. ‚Ä¢ Develop your social skills. Practice communicating effectively, building relationships, and resolving conflict. There are many resources available to help you improve your emotional intelligence. You can find books, articles, and even online courses on the topic. You can also work with a therapist or coach to develop your EI skills. Why is my alienated child not responding to my messages? A question I am often asked. No response to communications does not mean they don't want to reply or don't love you. Often the communications are highly monitored. Children are not armed with the tools to handle these very challenging situations. Some other reasons why they may not respond: Alienated children may fear the consequences or pressure from the alienating parent, who may actively discourage or even forbid communication with the alienated parent. This fear can be a significant barrier to responding to communication attempts. They may feel a strong sense of loyalty to the alienating parent and may perceive that responding to the alienated parent could be seen as disloyal. They may fear upsetting the favoured parent or experiencing negative consequences. In some cases, the alienating parent may manipulate or emotionally coerce the child into not responding to the other parent's attempts at communication. This manipulation can take the form of guilt, threats or emotional manipulation. Children in these situations often experience high levels of emotional distress and confusion. They may not respond due to their own emotional turmoil or feelings of being caught in the middle of a difficult situation. If the alienated child has been exposed to ongoing conflict and bitterness, they may have difficulty trusting the alienated parent's intentions or believing that communication will be positive or non-confrontational. Remember to self-care every day in every way possible. It is essential to incorporate self-care into your daily routines. It is like putting on a life vest whilst on a sinking ship. #alienatedchild #alienatingbehaviours #coercivecontrol #communications #childcoercivecontrol

With no end in sight, we are taking immediate action. Our goal right now is to channel funds to our partners on the ground in areas with the most desperate need. The notion of high-functioning anxiety comes from this conflict between the intense internal feelings and the ability to function despite those feelings. On the outside: A radiant smile, a meticulously organized desk, every task handled with precision. People might see a go-getter, a person who's got it all together. But beneath the surface: A mind racing at a million miles an hour, constant self-doubt, a fear of not being good enough, and sleepless nights worrying about the smallest details. High-functioning anxiety isn't always visible to the casual observer, but it‚Äôs a silent battle many face daily. It's a reminder that what we see on the surface doesn't always reflect the internal struggles someone is facing. Let's be kind, check in on our loved ones, and remember that understanding and support can make all the difference. üí™üß†‚ù§Ô∏è #Anxiety #mentalhealth #therapy #Anxietysupport

Red Eagle or William Weatherford (1780 or 1781 - March 24, 1824) was a Creek chief. One of many mixed-race descendants of Southeast Indians who intermarried with European traders and later colonial settlers. Red Eagle was of mixed Creek, French and Scots ancestry. He was raised as a Creek in the matrilineal nation and achieved his power in it, through his mother's prominent Wind Clan, as well as his father's trading connections. After showing his skill as a warrior, he was given the war name of Hopnicafutsahia. The Creek War (1813-1814), also known as the Red Stick War and the Creek Civil War, was a regional war between opposing Creek factions, European empires, and the United States, taking place largely in Alabama and along the Gulf Coast. Red Eagle became increasingly concerned about the influx of European Americans onto Creek land and eventually led a group known as ‚ÄúRed Sticks,‚Äù bent on protecting their land, their way of life, and their people from intruders. Eventually the smaller forces of Red Sticks and the larger opposing forces led by General Andrew Jackson came against each other. The conflict ended in the decisive defeat of the Red Sticks at The Battle of Horseshoe Bend, near modern-day Dadeville, Alabama. Terms were drawn up that provided far less land than the Creek tribe had previously held. The quote attributed to Chief Red Eagle reads, "Angry people want you to see how powerful they are. Loving people want you to see how powerful YOU are."-End ID]

#TheKnowledgeofGitaisNectar || Part - 21 Resolution of Doubt || Part-M In Gita Chapter 12 Verse 5, it is said that - "Those whose faith is in the Sachidanand Ghan Brahm (True-happiness-giving God), that is, in Param Akshar Brahm, and who only (chetsa) know Him, majority of the time (kleshH) because of doubt they are in a conflict of knowledge. Due to this, it is a salvation attained through suffering by those human beings." The meaning is that because of not finding a Tatvadarshi Saint (Complete Satguru), even Kabir Panthis (Gheesa Das Panthi, Garibdas Panthi, Dadu Panthi, Nekiram Panthi, all these are called Kabir Panthis) practice difficult religious austerity. They perform fasting, vow of silence and other difficult religious practices. Therefore, it is said that the way of worship of that Complete God is attained through hardships and miseries. But in reality, all the scripture-based way of worship is very easy. Evidence: - In Yajurved Chapter 40 Mantra 15, it is said about worship of Brahm that: - VaayuH anilam amritam ath idam bhasmantam shareeram | Om kritam smar, kilbey smar, kartuH smar || Meaning: - 'Om' naam is of Bramh worship. To get the amritam, that is, salvation obtained from it, chant 'Om' naam (vayuH anilam) through incoming and outgoing breath with full devotion until the end of the body (kritam smar) remember it while doing work, (kilbey smar) remember it with an ache, that is, with a pang in the heart, (KartuH smar) remember it considering it to be the main task of human life. (Yajurved Chapter 40 Mantra 15) Then Yajurved Chapter 40 Mantra 17, the speaker of the knowledge of Vedas (he is also the speaker of Gita) has stated that - 'That Complete God is hidden (unmanifested) in the upper lok (world). (Aham kham Brahm Om) I am Brahm; I live in divine sky-like Brahm Lok; my mantra is 'Om'. In Yajurved Chapter 40 Mantra 10, the speaker of the knowledge of Vedas says that - "Some consider God (Sambhavaat) to be in form who takes birth as an incarnation; some (asambhavaat) consider Him to be unborn, that is, formless. Whether that God takes birth or not or whatever He is like, (Dheeranam) Tatvadarshi Saints give that knowledge; (ShrunuH) listen from them. (Yajurved Chapter 40 Mantra 10) This same evidence is given in Gita Chapter 4 Verse 34 that the Tatvdarshi Saints impart the complete knowledge about God. Search for them; by asking them question without any deceit, politely and by prostrating before them, those Tatvdarshi saints will impart true spiritual knowledge to you. It is also mentioned in Sukshm Ved that: - Naam uthat naam baithat, naam sovat jaag re | Naam khaate naam peete, naam seti lag re || Meaning: - The worship of God is done only by chanting naam (mantra). Chant that naam (mantra) while doing your work, before falling asleep, as soon as you wake up in the morning, while having food, while drinking any liquid, that is, remember naam while doing all the tasks. A Stark Prediction: The Consequences of Falling for Media and Government Narratives In recent years, the world has been on a precipice, teetering between unity and division. The divisive narratives spun by media outlets and governments have only deepened the chasm. The Covid-19 pandemic was just the beginning, a precursor to the potential chaos that could ensue if we continue to be swayed by these narratives. If we allow ourselves to be continuously divided by the stories we are fed, the future looks bleak: 1. Deeper Erosion of Trust: As people become more polarized, trust in neighbors, friends, and even family will erode. Communities that once thrived on mutual respect and understanding will become hotbeds of suspicion and animosity. 2. Loss of Personal Freedoms: Governments, under the guise of "safety" and "security," will introduce more restrictive legislation. The rights and freedoms we hold dear could be curtailed, all in the name of a perceived greater good. 3. Economic Instability: A divided populace is easier to control, but it's also less productive and innovative. Economic downturns, job losses, and financial crises could become the norm rather than the exception. 4. Global Conflicts: The war between Israel and Palestine might be just the tip of the iceberg. As countries take sides and alliances shift, the world could be dragged into a devastating global conflict, the likes of which we've never seen. 5. Social Unrest: Protests, riots, and civil unrest could become commonplace. Streets that once echoed with laughter and joy might reverberate with the sounds of anger and despair. 6. Mental Health Crisis: The constant barrage of negative news, coupled with the loss of social connections, could lead to a significant rise in mental health issues. Depression, anxiety, and other disorders might become rampant. This is not a future any of us want. But it's a future that could very well become a reality if we continue to let divisive narratives dictate our beliefs and actions. It's a call to action for every individual: question everything, seek the truth, and prioritize unity and understanding above all else. The fate of our world hinges on our ability to see through the smoke and mirrors and come together as one. Copied from Tom m.
