14-year-old Klondike entered Riverside Shelter in May as a severely matted and flea-infested stray. After he was euth-listed, we put a hold on him and began arranging for his exit. We put out a plea for volunteers to do his freedom ride, which Jayne Kleinfeld saw while she was sitting on the Frosted Faces Foundation‚Äôs porch while waiting for her Frosted Face Beck and Charlie‚Äôs vet appointments. She offered to go get him and brought him down to us safely. Jayne found that she couldn‚Äôt stop thinking about Klondike and came back to scoop him up for a Fling that same week! After their two-week Fling was up and she brought him back to Frosted Faces Foundation, she was completely devastated and cried every day! She missed him so much and ultimately realized that she couldn‚Äôt imagine not being his family. Jayne made it official and adopted Klondike! Here is an update on how he is doing: ‚ÄúKlondike has settled in fantastically! I initially took him on a Fling before I adopted him, and within a few hours of being here, he had become my shadow and was following me everywhere. He's super low maintenance and has been a joy to have around. He always gets rave remarks on how sweet and calm he is when he visits the Frosted Faces vet staff for appointments! It was a little bit of an adjustment for my non-Frosted Face Farrah to get used to him at first. To be clear, this was a one-sided feud that Farrah instigated - Klondike did absolutely nothing wrong! I think Farrah was just intimidated by him because he's a little bit bigger than her and she felt that her alpha status was being threatened. It's now been a few months, and while they're not besties, they coexist just fine with little conflict! His favorite food is everything, and his favorite activity is napping! He's pretty low-energy and just enjoys sleeping for most of the day, which means that he fits in perfectly with my Frosted Face's Beck and Charlie (formerly Domingo)! He wasn't feeling too good at the beginning of last month, so I took him to see Dr. Russell, who discovered that he had a foreign body that was causing an intestinal blockage. He had surgery at Anicira the next morning, where they ended up removing a small rock from his stomach. His recovery was rough. He wouldn't eat for about a week after the surgery, and I had to bring him back to the vet multiple times to try and get his appetite back. Then, his incision site got infected badly, and he had to go back to Anicira to be put under anesthesia for a second time so that they could open the site back up and clean out the area. He was such a trooper! Thankfully, his incision site healed well the second time and he is back to his normal self! When someone mentions they would like to adopt, I ALWAYS mention how amazing Frosted Faces is and how rewarding it is to give a senior pet a home. There's a reason why so many Frosted Faces families are loyal adopters who have adopted multiple Frosted Faces! This rescue is just the best, and I'm so thankful to be able to be a part of it!‚Äù Family: Jayne Kleinfeld Fans: Kelly Nielsen and The Mendoza Family Facts: Klondike is 14 years old and was rescued from Riverside Shelter on May 15, 2023.

15 lessons from Emotional Intelligence: Why It Can Matter More Than IQ by Daniel Goleman: 1. Emotional intelligence (EI) is the ability to understand and manage your own emotions, as well as the emotions of others. 2. EI is just as important for success in life as IQ, and perhaps even more so. 3. EI consists of five key skills: self-awareness, self-regulation, motivation, empathy, and social skills. 4. Self-awareness is the ability to recognize and understand your own emotions. 5. Self-regulation is the ability to manage your emotions and impulses. 6. Motivation is the ability to set and achieve goals. 7. Empathy is the ability to understand and share the feelings of others. 8. Social skills are the ability to build and maintain relationships. 9. EI can be learned and improved over time. 10. EI can help you succeed in all areas of your life, including your personal relationships, your career, and your health. 11. EI can help you make better decisions. When you are aware of your own emotions and the emotions of others, you are better able to weigh all of the factors involved in a decision. 12. EI can help you resolve conflict more effectively. When you can understand and empathize with the other person's perspective, you are more likely to find a solution that works for everyone. 13. EI can help you build stronger relationships. When you are able to communicate your own emotions clearly and understand the emotions of others, you are more likely to build trust and intimacy. 14. EI can help you manage stress and anxiety. When you are able to identify and manage your own emotions, you are better able to cope with stressful situations. 15. EI can lead to better physical health. Studies have shown that people with high EI are less likely to suffer from heart disease, stroke, and other chronic health conditions. How to improve your emotional intelligence: ‚Ä¢ Pay attention to your emotions. Notice how you feel throughout the day and try to identify the triggers that cause your emotions to change. ‚Ä¢ Label your emotions. Once you can identify your emotions, put a name to them. This will help you to better understand what you are feeling and why. ‚Ä¢ Manage your emotions. Once you understand your emotions, you can develop strategies for managing them in a healthy way. For example, if you are feeling angry, you might try taking a few deep breaths or going for a walk. ‚Ä¢ Empathize with others. Try to put yourself in the shoes of others and see things from their perspective. This will help you to better understand their feelings and motivations. ‚Ä¢ Develop your social skills. Practice communicating effectively, building relationships, and resolving conflict. There are many resources available to help you improve your emotional intelligence. You can find books, articles, and even online courses on the topic. You can also work with a therapist or coach to develop your EI skills. We always read parashat Bereshit on the Sabbath following the holiday of Simchat Torah, and therefore it begins the Torah reading sequence for the new Jewish year.... Right at the outset of the narrative of the Torah, then, we will read about the ‚Äúproto-euangelion,‚Äù or the ‚Äúfirst gospel‚Äù message of God‚Äôs redemption given through the Promised Seed of Eve... ==== The very first prophecy of the Torah concerns the promise of the coming ‚ÄúSeed of the woman‚Äù who would vanquish the serpent (nachash) that had originally tempted and deceived Eve (Gen. 3:15). This prophecy is sometimes called the proto-euangelion (‚Äúfirst gospel‚Äù), since it is the starting point of all subsequent prophecy and redemptive history revealed in the Scriptures. Indeed, since the mystery of the Incarnation of God the Son (the ‚ÄúSon of Man‚Äù) is foreshadowed here, this prophecy is linked to the original woman, Eve. Just as Eve became a carrier of the corruption of human nature by heeding the voice of the tempter, so she would be the carrier of God Himself for the deliverance of mankind through the advent of the Redeemer. In the tragic aftermath of the transgression of the first man and woman, then, God first announced His unfailing redemptive love for the human race that would culminate in the birth, sacrifice, and resurrection of Yeshua our Savior and Deliverer - ‚Äúborn of a woman, born under the law‚Äù (Gal. 4:4). Our restoration begins with God‚Äôs love and passion. God's first question to Adam after he broke covenant was: "Where (◊ê÷∑◊ô÷º÷∂◊õ÷º÷∏◊î) are you?" - the voice of a loving Father in search of his son (Gen. 3:9). Of course God knew exactly how his son was attempting to hide, though He almost acted as if He was unwilling to believe that he would betray his love by disobeying His commandment. Therefore God‚Äôs poignant question was directed to Adam‚Äôs heart: ‚ÄúOh my son, how did you get to this place?‚Äù God was giving Adam an opportunity to turn back to Him, to confess the sin, to undergo teshuvah, to become reconciled... This is the necessary prelude to any honest relationship with God. Recall that the original promise of the coming Savior was given within the context of the curse and judgment upon Satan: "I will put enmity between you and the woman, and between your seed and her seed; he shall crush your head, and you shall crush his heel" (Gen. 3:15). That God‚Äôs promise was first directed to Satan is surely by design, since he ‚Äúleft his first estate‚Äù by becoming the ‚Äúmonster in the garden‚Äù and was therefore primarily responsible for the transgression of Adam and Eve in the first place (Ezek. 28:13-15,19). The promise delivered to Satan was therefore one of coming retribution and divine judgment: Evil would not have the last word in the matter of mankind, and therefore Satan‚Äôs schemes would be avenged by God in the fullness of time (Gal. 4:4-5). Notice, however, that Adam and Eve were not yet judged for their sin when the LORD God gave the promise of the coming of the Redeemer. Before a word of judgment was directed toward them, God‚Äôs love and light was already revealed. Indeed, immediately after their judgment was pronounced, ‚Äúthe LORD God made tunics of skin for Adam and his wife and clothed them‚Äù (Gen. 3:21) - a clear picture of being compassionately ‚Äúrobed in righteousness‚Äù imparted by an innocent sacrifice. The very first sacrifice recorded in the Torah - performed by God Himself - prefigured the coming redemption by the ‚Äúseed of the woman‚Äù who would die as a substitutionary sacrifice for their sins, and therefore Yeshua is rightly called "the Lamb slain from the foundation (or beginning) of the world" (Rev. 13:8). This further explains why Eve‚Äôs son (Abel) offered a blood sacrifice that was accepted by the LORD, whereas Cain‚Äôs offering the ‚Äúfruit of the earth‚Äù was rejected. The very first prophecy of Torah therefore describes - in the most succinct form - the coming of the Savior and the great conflict of the ages. First, God declares that He would put enmity (◊ê÷µ◊ô◊ë÷∏◊î) between Satan and the woman. This enmity, or ‚Äúhostile hatred,‚Äù was based on the memory of Eve‚Äôs misguided trust she evidenced in the garden. When Eve first sympathetically listened to the lies of the nachash (serpent), she immediately began her descent into exile and became a temptress herself. Her first step toward sin was a gullibility or openness that ultimately resulted in a lack of trust of God (which is part of the reason why we must be saved by trusting, as a ‚Äúlike-for-like‚Äù reversal of the original sin). At the very dawn of human history, then, we see that ‚Äútruth‚Äù (◊ê÷±◊û÷∂◊™) apart from God (◊ê) leads to death (◊û÷µ◊™). Eve was deceived because of Satan, but Adam deliberately chose to disobey God (2 Cor. 11:3; 1 Tim 2:14). In response to her teshuvah (repentance), God blessed Eve before He judged her by imparting to her a God-given hatred for Satan and his lies, as well as the promise that she would take part in the birth of the Savior of mankind. One week ago today was the opening of the ◊î◊™◊ñ◊û◊ï◊®◊™ ◊î◊°◊ô◊û◊§◊ï◊†◊ô◊™ ◊ô◊®◊ï◊©◊ú◊ô◊ù Jerusalem Symphony Orchestra season. Friends from all over Israel and Europe joined me in celebrating my first week as Music Director of this wonderful orchestra. I was overjoyed to share the stage with the incredible musicians, meet the wonderful audience, and work alongside our dedicated team at the orchestra. We continued on with a second celebratory concert in Tel Aviv on Thursday. On Saturday morning, my wife Sarah and I woke up to the sound of explosions near our hotel. Soon enough, sirens were heard and we spent the day with my parents in and out of the bomb shelter in the basement of our hotel. Thanks to the kind help of friends in Israel, my family and I were able to secure seats on a flight home to Vienna on Sunday. I am at a complete loss for words as my friends, extended family, and the musicians of the Jerusalem Symphony Orchestra, are still in Israel, facing unimaginable uncertainty and danger. I'm left speechless, overwhelmed with anger, shock, disbelief, and profound concern, distraught for my new musical family. A week that was meant to be a celebration of music and togetherness has been overshadowed by the harsh reality of terrorism and conflict. My thoughts are with Israel, and with all those who are enduring the unimaginable. It is impossible to know what to say or what to do. I hope for the safety of the people living through this hell, and send my deepest condolences to those who have lost friends and family in the most horrific of circumstances.

NFF and Togo Football Federation fight over possession of Gift Orban. Togo football federation has taken steps to stop Gift Orban's involvement with the Nigerian national team, with claims that Orban is of Togolese nationality and therefore eligible to represent Togo at the international competition.. Report suggested that Orban's exclusion from the Super Eagles' Squad for November friendly is stems from an ongoing national dispute where Nigerian football federation (NFF) received correspondence from the Togolese FA asserting that Orban is of Togolese nationality. To avoid potential conflict with FIFA regulations, NFF has opted not to invite Gift Orban to the national team pending when the issue will be resolved. Rhoda Etuk.

# *In the vast tapestry of human existence, a profound battle is unfolding, one that holds the power to mold our collective destiny. In the midst of a world where the allure of the mundane and superficial often captures our attention, a significant segment of humanity has awoken to a deeper calling.* # *This current struggle is far more than a physical conflict; it is a battle of ideals, a war waged between the forces of an entrenched elite and the impassioned champions of liberation. What lies at the core of this monumental clash is the progression of the human spirit towards a higher plane of existence.* # *In the shadows of history's stage, the sparks of spiritual evolution are already ignited. A growing consensus among individuals echoes with the weariness of superfluous conflicts, the burdens of totalitarian rule, and the shackles of authoritarian control. The time has arrived for humanity to reclaim the limitless power that resides within each soul, to unlock the doors of the self-imposed mental prison, and to bask in the radiant illumination of unfettered freedom.* # *Picture, if you will, the dawn of a new era, where the resonance of unity transcends the discord of division. It is a time when the heart and soul of humanity sing in harmony, awakening to the profound interconnectedness that binds us all. The pursuit of materialism, celebrity obsession, and the trivial distractions of the Kardashian dynasty lose their allure, as individuals rediscover their spiritual essence.* # *With each step taken on this path of enlightenment, we move closer to realizing the profound truth that we are not mere bystanders in the unfolding drama of existence. We are the architects of our destinies, co-creators of a world founded on love, compassion, and the profound realization of our interconnectedness.* # *The great war that shapes the future of human existence is, at its essence, a war of consciousness. It is an awakening to the power that resides within us, the power to reshape the world, to transcend the limitations that have bound us, and to emerge as beings of boundless potential.* # *As we embark on this transformative journey, may the light of awareness guide our steps and may the fires of spiritual evolution burn ever brighter within our hearts and souls. It is a journey toward freedom, unity, and the reclamation of our infinite power.* # *James William Kaler*

üá≤üáπ We are back on home soil! üá≤üáπ Damaged & Co. would like to thank Malta's Ambassador to Israel, Her Excellency Cecilia Attard Pirotta, for her constant support and aid we found from her in our time of turmoil. Her Excellency was with us every step of the way, and we are eternally grateful. Heartfelt thanks to our brother Tamir Khan who, notwithstanding his personal situation, offered his invaluable support through thick and thin. Also, Shay Daudi for his hospitality and generosity, and all the people who helped us make it through this difficult time. Our gratitude goes to Hades management, Rene Farrugia, who helped us organize this tour and was a constant support throughout. Our journey started on an excellent note with the event at the Wunderbar Club, Haifa. We immensely enjoyed our time there with Proxy , ZedDestructive and a very warm crowd. The management and staff of the club were the perfect hosts. Another memorable evening was at The Wave Club in Tel Aviv. Such amazing people. From there, everything changed with a dramatic fashion. Due to the situation, the gigs in Tel Aviv, with our brothers of Interia and Jerusalem with Xoter, Goregamel and Paranoid Existence were cancelled while we safely waited for development and started working on ways to get out of Israel. Our thoughts go to our friends in Israel. May you and your loved ones be safe. You are in our hearts, thoughts and prayers. Thank you to all who showed concern and offered support for our difficult situation. Above all, our families and loved ones who had to go through this ordeal with us. No words of gratitude will ever be enough. Our thoughts remain with our friends who are still caught in the conflict. Our plight might be over but theirs is ongoing. May this conflict be resolved in the shortest time possible so that no more blood is spilled. Heartfelt thanks, Damaged & Co. #Damagedandco #IsraelTour #HadesManagement #metalband #metaltour #AlternativeMetal

The political gamesmanship by the GOP in Washington continues apace over the terrorist attack out of Gaza. In my piece yesterday, I touched upon three aspects of this: misinformation over the Iranian deal, blaming the White House for failure of intel, and the current paralysis and lack of House leadership in Congress.

Today, I unfortunately need to add three more things to that list. First, Republicans opened a new line of attack on Monday by implying that President Biden has been absent and unresponsive to the crisis. Second, right-wing agitators, from Elon Musk to Eric Trump, have been busily spreading misinformation and anti-semitism. And third, with a hold still in place on many diplomatic appointments, led by Sen. Rand Paul and others in the Senate, the State Department has been hampered at the very time key regional leadership is needed.

Let‚Äôs dive into these and the politics of the crisis as it plays out here in the U.S. in Part 2 of this series (which I hope is actually over after today).

**‚ÄúWhere is President Biden?‚Äù

The right is convinced that Joe Biden doesn‚Äôt have the stamina and leadership qualities to see us through an international crisis, and so they predictably push narratives that fit that false claim. With respect to the Gaza crisis, they claimed on Fox and across social media that Biden was largely absent from the scene.

‚ÄúWhere is President Biden?‚Äù demanded former Trump press secretary Ari Fleishcher.

‚ÄúPresident Biden is nowhere to be seen and nothing to say,‚Äù declared Sen. Tom Cotton (R-AR).

The criticism grew out of the White House calling a ‚Äúlid‚Äù yesterday with the press just before noon. Critics immediately went on the attack.

‚ÄúWith war raging in Israel, the White House called a lid for Joe Biden at 11:46am,‚Äù said Fox anchor John Roberts on the X platform. Roberts of course is a seasoned anchor and knows that a lid is not what he implied by this statement.

White nationalist and former White House advisor Stephen Miller falsely stated, ‚ÄúA lid means reporters can go home because no more news is happening. You won‚Äôt miss anything. The day is done.‚Äù He added, ‚ÄúIn this case, it probably means President Biden is taking a nap.‚Äù

More responsible and reasonable voices, however, hit back with the truth. Citing Miller‚Äôs statement, legal analyst Joyce Vance noted, ‚ÄúThe term ‚Äòa lid‚Äô appears to have meant something very different in the Trump administration. Perhaps Stephen Miller reveals too much when he suggests it means the president is napping? Joe Biden is almost certainly in the situation room & otherwise staying on top of the conflict.‚Äù

White House spokesman John Kirby pushed back on Fox‚Äôs questions about the ‚Äúlid,‚Äù reminding that the fact that the President has no public events doesn‚Äôt mean he‚Äôs not working. ‚ÄúHe is working. He stayed updated throughout the day. He will be talking to foreign leaders,‚Äù Kirby clarified.

Indeed, later in the day, a remarkable joint statement on Israel emerged from the five leaders of France, Germany, Italy, the U.K. and the U.S. It is both forceful and nuanced, and it included the following clear statement and warning to third party actors:

‚ÄúWe make clear that the terrorist actions of Hamas have no justification, no legitimacy, and must be universally condemned. There is never any justification for terrorism.  In recent days, the world has watched in horror as Hamas terrorists massacred families in their homes, slaughtered over 200 young people enjoying a music festival, and kidnapped elderly women, children, and entire families, who are now being held as hostages.

Our countries will support Israel in its efforts to defend itself and its people against such atrocities. We further emphasize that this is not a moment for any party hostile to Israel to exploit these attacks to seek advantage.

All of us recognize the legitimate aspirations of the Palestinian people, and support equal measures of justice and freedom for Israelis and Palestinians alike. But make no mistake: Hamas does not represent those aspirations, and it offers nothing for the Palestinian people other than more terror and bloodshed.‚Äù

In short, the White House called a ‚Äúlid‚Äù and made no public appearances because it was doing the hard work of international diplomacy. The attacks by the GOP during a time of crisis continue to undermine U.S. foreign interests and present an opening for our enemies to exploit.

Words matter. A number of media organisations have editorial guidelines directing them not to use the term 'terrorist' in their reporting of the conflict between Israel and Hamas. These guidelines may be borne out of well-intentioned aspirations to appear accurate and impartial. But there is a point at which the failure to use the term 'terrorist', is itself a failure of accuracy and impartiality. The depth of the terror that Hamas has inflicted upon innocent people across Israel in recent days is not in doubt. The murder of babies where they sleep is not the act of a 'freedom fighter'. The performative desecration of dead bodies for the benefit of social media, the rape of women and the beheading of civilians in their homes, are not the acts of 'militants'. The true motives of Hamas could not be clearer. It seeks the murder of Jews and the annihilation of the Jewish state. Their charter says as much. Hamas is no different to ISIS. Did decent, moral people seek to justify the actions of 9/11, 7/7 or the Manchester Arena bombing? It should be painfully obvious that there is no moral equivalence between those whose motive is to deliberately target innocent civilians in cold blood, and those whose motive is to remove the threat of such murderers. The fact that this discussion is necessary at all is a clear sign that we are losing our moral compass and of the warped nature of the depths to which discourse on Israel has sunk. And so I call upon broadcasters to urgently change the way they describe Hamas. Further, I call upon all decent people to have the courage to call out this terror for what it is. We must all be unequivocal that the loss of any innocent life is a tragedy, and that the barbaric, murderous terrrorism of Hamas cannot be denied or obfuscated. It is a matter of deepest regret that some feel otherwise. This is not 'resistance' or 'struggle'. It is terrorism. To purposefully avoid that word is to wilfully mislead.

Yan Senior in Mawab, Davao De Oro on October 9, 2023. PFC Perdido fearlessly pursued a snatcher who stole the wallet of Mrs. Lorife Ulep, containing P30,000.00 as payment for her daughter's hospital bill at Aquino Hospital, Tagum City, on September 28. PFC Perdido's heroic act did not involve actual conflict but rather a life-threatening risk as he chased and apprehended the snatcher hiding in a nearby village despite the potential danger. Brigadier General Allan D Hambala, Acting Commander of the 10th Infantry (Agila) Division, personally pinned the medal on PFC Perdido and subsequently commended his heroism and dedication to duty. In an interview, Mr. Efren Ulep, the victim's husband, expressed his gratitude for PFC Perdido's heroism. "Mabuti sir at may tumulong. Hindi na man siya duty diba, pero si sir (referring to PFC Perdido) ginamit niya ang sinumpaan niya," Mr. Ulep said in vernacular. PFC Perdido is a member of the Morale and Welfare Recovery Center of the 10IMB under the Operational Control of the 10ID. Israel forms emergency government against Hamas as deaths and damage in Gaza mount Israel formed an emergency unity government on Wednesday as its jets pounded Gaza and tanks massed around the densely populated Palestinian enclave while Hamas militants said they were still fighting on Israeli territory following their shock weekend incursion. Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu agreed to form a war cabinet with former defence minister and centrist opposition party leader Benny Gantz and focus entirely on the conflict, a joint statement from Gantz's National Unity party said. Israel's death toll rose to 1,200 with over 2,700 wounded, its military said, from Hamas militants' hours-long rampage after breaching the fence enclosing Gaza on Saturday. U.S. President Joe Biden has issued a warning seemingly aimed at Hamas' Iranian supporters not to exploit the Gaza conflagration to start a wider Middle East war. Israeli reprisal strikes on blockaded Gaza have killed 1,100 people and wounded 5,339, Gaza's Health Ministry said. Some 535 residential buildings had been destroyed leaving around 250,000 homeless, Hamas officials said. Most of the displaced were in U.N.-designated shelters, others huddling in shattered streets. The group's armed wing, the Al Qassam Brigades, said it was still fighting inside Israel on Wednesday. Israel deployed tanks and armoured vehicles just north of Gaza where the clashes were reported, but had no immediate comment on the Hamas claim. Later in the day, alerts warning of incoming aircraft were issued across northern Israel, well removed from Gaza in the south, but the Israeli military subsequently said these may have been a malfunction. A Reuters TV crew saw a house hit by an apparent projectile near Metulla in Israel's far north, close to the border with south Lebanon where the heavily armed Iran-backed Hezbollah group is active. Hamas's armed wing said it had targeted the northern Israeli coastal city of Haifa with an R60 rocket. There were no immediate reports of casualties after sirens sounded in Haifa and nearby towns. Israel has vowed swift punishment for the deadliest Palestinian militant attack in its 75-year history, which left corpses strewn around a music festival and a kibbutz community. The military said dozens of its fighter jets struck more than 200 targets in a neighbourhood of Gaza City overnight that it said had been used by Hamas to launch its attacks. "We started the offensive from the air, later on we will also come from the ground," Defence Minister Yoav Gallant told soldiers near the fence on Tuesday. Israel has put Gaza under "total siege" to stop food and fuel reaching the enclave of 2.3 million people, many poor and dependent on aid. Hamas media said on Wednesday electricity went out after the only power station stopped working. With Palestinian rescue workers overwhelmed, others in the crowded coastal strip joined the search for bodies in rubble. "I was sleeping here when the house collapsed on top of me," one man cried as he and others used flashlights on the stairs of a building hit by missiles to find anyone trapped. The Israeli military said its troops had killed at least 1,000 Palestinian gunmen who infiltrated from Gaza and the Chief of the General Staff met commanders to discuss their next steps. My husband was looking into Ricardo Sotil who is running for First Selectman. He noticed Rick has said in multiple meetings that he resides at 426 South Grand St. As we live around the corner, he questioned how this building could possibly be a residence. It has been a commercial building used by Sotil Tree for a long time. The Town does not allow for commercial and residential at the same property. My husband did a FOIA with the Town for all records and correspondence for that address and he came across this information. As you can see, Rick was told to vacate the building as a use of residence by the building department back in July. He still states this address in Town meetings. Upon further investigation, my husband looked up, on the Secretary of State website the annual filing's for Rick's businesses. As you can see he certified and stated under the penalties of false statements that he resides at 6 Valley View Dr, East Granby. He listed his business address as 426 South Grand St, Suffield and his mailing address as a p.o. box in East Granby. How can Rick claim to live in Suffield when he also claims to be a resident of East Granby? Per section 202 of the Town Charter this should make him ineligible. Rick has either lied under penalty of false statement to the State of CT in his business filings or is lying to State of CT in his campaign filings and also lying to the residents of this Town. The evidence is very clear from these documents. Furthermore, one of Rick's claims is that he is running as an unaffiliated. Did you know not more than 6 months ago he was a registered Democrat in East Granby? He attended numerous Suffield Democrat Town Committee (DTC) meetings for the past year in hopes to secure their nomination. The DTC refused to nominate him. Why? He claims no party politics. Didn't seem that way a couple months ago. Rick is also suing the Town because he was denied by the Planning and Zoning Commission and Zoning Board of Appeals in regards to his request for growing Marijuana at his "residence/business." The Town created a special zoning ordinance for this. Why doesn't Rick just follow these regulations? Is this a direct conflict of interest for him to run for the Town's top elected position? Is his goal here to try to settle his own case? Isn't it convenient that his timing on this matter and effort to run for this position line up perfectly? In addition, Rick's campaign has been assisted by the Hornish's whose dog mauled an elderly woman to death and also have a lawsuit against the Town. Is this an attempt by them to have the suits settle in their interests? Rick claims he's all for transparency yet these facts tell a different story. Suffield residents deserve better than Rick Sotil and his lies.

Reactive vs. Receptive State of Mind Daniel Siegel, in his book ‚ÄúThe Whole-Brain Child,‚Äù talks about when the children are on guard, defensive, or angry, they are in a reactive state of mind. They interpret everything negatively and are not receptive to the positive. In the heat of the moment, it is not time to rationalize with the child, scold, or counsel them. They are too reactive (emotional) to look at things rationally. They are operating from their ‚Äúemotional brain,‚Äù not their ‚Äúthinking, reasoning brain.‚Äù Some children are in the on-guard, reactive state of mind most of the time. Because of either biological makeup or past experiences, they do not feel safe, are on high alert, and are always looking for the negative. They walk through life with filtered glasses on, looking for, and interpreting things in a negative light. Usually, these children have poor self-esteem and tend to look for negative intent from others. I see this a lot in autistic children. Not necessary the negativism (although in some yes), but being emotionally ‚Äúreactive,‚Äù and less often in a ‚Äúreceptive‚Äù state of mind. Autistic children will often freak when things don‚Äôt go according to their expectations and view every little change as a threat to their existence. Uncertainty drives them nuts. They need predictability and must control everything they do to maintain that predictability. They are on-guard and anxious and quickly panic when things don‚Äôt go according to plan. They are quick to react from their emotional part of the brain, with little mediation from the thinking brain. Research has shown that autistic individuals have a higher level of stress (anxiety) chemicals in their nervous system, even during a resting state. These high levels of stress chemicals leave the nervous on high-alert for threat! When they are hyper-vigilant for threat, they will be looking for the negative and react quickly to stay safe (reactive state of mind). They are going to react quickly and intensively, often over-reacting to the conflict. This hyper-reactive state is natural, given their sensory, emotional, and social processing difficulties. Between sensory bombardment and overload that leaves their nervous systems vulnerable to insult and the constant difficulties understanding and regulating with others, their nervous systems are on ‚Äúhigh alert‚Äù and ready to react, to stay safe. This hyper-alertness is an instinctual mechanism in the brain to be ‚Äúon guard‚Äù when possible threat is near. The brain is ready to ‚Äúfight or flee‚Äù at any moment. When the possibility of sensory insult and social discourse is frequently present, the nervous system becomes conditioned to be in a ‚Äúreactive‚Äù mode most of the time. What to do. 1. Know your child‚Äôs state of mind. Know what state of mind (brain) your child is operating from. What are they like when ‚Äúreceptive,‚Äù and what are they like when ‚Äúreactive.‚Äù When they are in a defensive, reactive state, it is not the time to ‚Äúcommand and demand.‚Äù It is only going to push their panic button. It is not the time to tell them what and why because they are not receptive to listening. Listen to their perspective and validate their feelings before trying to negotiate. Try not to reason with them verbally, convince them that they are wrong, or do things differently. Wait until the child is calm and in a receptive state to collaborate. 2. A good portion of angry outbursts from children are when adults ignore this principle and try to demand and direct, scold, or counsel the child when they are emotionally in turmoil. Like Dr. Ross Greene, author of ‚ÄúThe Explosive Child,‚Äù states, ‚ÄúMost problems don‚Äôt come from a rigid and inflexible child alone, but when a rigid/inflexible child meets a rigid/inflexible adult.‚Äù (Paraphrase) We must be the flexible ones to bring the child to a flexible (receptive) state. 3. It is important to help the child feel safe, accepted, and competent throughout the day, so their nervous system is less defensive and more receptive. Help the child obtain a receptive state of mind and keep them there. All the toolbox strategies on this page are focused on moving the child from the defensive/reactive mode to a safe and receptive state. Understand and respect the child‚Äôs comfort zones and help them feel competent stretching these comfort zones. 4. When emotions are flying, in the heat of the moment, respond to the ‚Äúfeelings‚Äù first, then the behavior. When the child is upset, do not scold, counsel, demand, or teach when emotional. As discussed before, acknowledge and validate the feelings behind the behavior first before dealing with the behavior. You don‚Äôt have to agree with the behavior; just validate the feelings behind the behavior. Once the emotion subsides, then collaborate. Of course, if the behavior is dangerous, you must block and interrupt the behavior, but then focus on tackling the feelings before discussing how to deal with the behavior. In a recent update on the ongoing Israel-Palestinian conflict, the safety of the Bnei Menashe community in Israel, an ethnic Mizo Jewish group, has been a topic of concern. The Mizos reached out to inquire about the Bnei Menashe's well-being amidst the continuing hostilities. Reports indicate that, while the Bnei Menashe are spread across Israel, the majority reside in the northern part of the country, which has, thankfully, been spared from rocket attacks. As per available information, no casualties have been reported within the community. However, there is an unconfirmed report of a Bnei Menashe woman remaining missing since Saturday. Like other communities in Israel, the Bnei Menashe youths, who serve as reservists and in active roles within the Israeli Defence Forces, have been called up for duty. So far, there are no reports of casualties among them. The ongoing conflict between Hamas and Israel has resulted in a tragic toll, with at least 2055 lives lost in just five days. Gaza Strip has faced constant bombardment from Israel, while Israeli cities near the Gaza Strip continue to endure rocket attacks. The Bnei Menashe, a sub-group of the Mizo community who follow Judaism, are the second-largest Mizo ethno-religious group after the Mizo Christians. Like other ethnic Jews, they are entitled to make Aliyah, which is the Jewish concept of returning to Israel, and immigrate into the country as recognized ethnic Jews. This privilege is not extended to most other communities claiming Jewish ancestry. Currently, several thousand Bnei Menashe have made Israel their home, while many others continue to live in India alongside Mizo Christians. #israelnews #Palestinians #Mizoram #themizos

Every 2 - 2.3 years a new set of problems and troubles appear to mobilize the world and our minds and energy. This corresponds to the cycle of Mars. When Mars joins the Sun a new Mars pattern is imprinted. Let‚Äôs look back in the last few years. In September 2019- Mars Joins the Sun in Virgo- the sign of health and disease- we know what followed in the next 2.5 years‚Ä¶. All focus was on the pandemic. In October 2021 Mars joined the Sun in Libra, pretty much within 4-5 months the focus shifted from illness to war / peace (Libra). The following 2 years the world split into 2 factions. New powerful economic alliances started forming: western countries vs Brics and the East. But Libra is a more gentle sign, it never grew into a big world conflict. There was more of an re-arrangement of trading alliances and economic powers. (Libra) Now we are on the verge of a new Mars cycle and we see the shifting energies. Just less than a month before the Mars conjunction with the Sun in Scorpio, the war in the Middle East erupted. Scorpio is a way more ruthless and deadly sign. The diplomatic gloves of Libra come off, no more negotiations, political and economic sanctions and such, now a real threat and destructive approach is forming. There are calls to arms, mobilizing multiple countries, calls for no mercy and total annihilation. Both sides are in a deadly grip. Extreme response and deeply emotional reaction becomes the norm, clouding reason, spurred by revenge and power. There are hidden forces and motives at work too. Scorpio rules the vested and hidden interests of a small powerful faction. While Libra cycle was able to keep the balance, Scorpio cycle is all or nothing. War, destruction, purging‚Ä¶ are qualifies Scorpio carries. Will humanity be able to keep it humaneness?! Rebirth after destruction and total transformation is also Scorpio.

Our thoughts are with all people affected. Let‚Äôs hold space and compassion for the people of Palestinian and the Jewish community through this time as we work to continually center humanity.

‚ÄúMourning for the people of Palestine and the Jewish community, both communities who have shown up for the liberation of Black people for decades.
Navigating how to be an ally if you aren‚Äôt in either community is complex and I encourage you to center humanity during this time. Continue to speak against violence. Don‚Äôt get swept up in talking points.
If you don‚Äôt know what to say, know this. Your Palestinian friends are looking to you to know you see their humanity and right to a life without disenfranchisement. Your Jewish friends are looking to you to know you do not support the loss of innocent Jewish lives and that their Jewish identity does not mean they support the actions of the Israeli government. Your Palestinian friends are looking at you to demonstrate you don‚Äôt equate their existence to hamas and that additional innocent people shouldn‚Äôt face starvation, continuous violence and the stripping of their human rights. While your Jewish friends also want you to know their grief may be complex, and they deserve time to process, and that their mourning is not an endorsement of violence. Their fear and grief is valid and has a historical basis.
While there are loud extremists, there are even more people who are scared and trying to process - figuring out how to take action, how to grieve, and wondering how this can stop.
You can be critical of hamas and the Israeli government while holding space and compassion for Jewish and Palestinian people.
We need a solution that centers humanity. We cannot continue to justify any type of human rights violations.
And we must confront the reality that the failure to solve this conflict has allowed tension to boil in a way that‚Äôs putting innocent people at risk.‚Äù

Sometimes silence is cowardice. Sometimes silence is presence. 

When Audre Lorde said, ‚Äúyour silence will not protect you‚Äù, she was speaking to people who have been silenced but had something to say. It was not a mandate to speak and center your own barely-formed opinions in the midst of every conflict. And it certainly was not a mandate to perform your pain or outrage in the public theater that is social media. 

Social media deceives us into thinking it is the supreme form of expression and justice work. But these spaces were not made to care for and protect Black women. And sometimes silence in this space frees you up to advocate better and with more sincerity and curiosity in another space. It does not mean silence in total. Do what feels just and sincere through whatever medium feels just and sincere.

"Soon a war will cover the world in ashes, and it is the task of the awakened to find the spark to rekindle the sacred fire."

Message from Melchizedek, priest of Jerusalem, on Mount Tabor, Israel. Two weeks ago.

As he covered me in ashes, he described the approaching war, telling us over and over again to get out of there, that our mission was Egypt.

His words were clear: "when you see the ashes of war, look within and seek your inner spark to light the world in light. Maintain that internal fire in the face of conflict. The last thing we need is fear and judgment".

Those who are attacking Israel today are not the Palestinian people, who live with Jews and Christians and follow Allah's message of unity.
Those who are attacking are terrorists.

No political vision can justify what is being experienced. This is not a war between two peoples, it is a terrorist group causing the death of its own and others.

May the ashes that fall on this earth ignite the spark of hearts.

As I watch the carnage and the slow death of the people in Gaza unfold I hear the silence of cowards and I see the apathy of the heartless. I also see the hidden hand of the mainstream media. The 4th Branch is hard at work once again.¬†

2 days ago a report that was repeated until it didn‚Äôt matter if it was true anymore was debunked. The Israeli Army has admitted it has no confirmation of any babies, let alone 40 babies being decapitated. I remember after 9/11 there was a video circulating of Palestinians ‚Äúcheering the towers coming down.‚Äù It sparked anger and vitriol from Americans. And it was a fake too. The video was from 1992 with children cheering Arafats return from exile. How easily we are manipulated. This doesn‚Äôt mean that there are no crimes of war. When war comes morals are gone and there is only death, chaos and murder.¬†

I also want to point out that framing this as a ‚Äúreligious conflict‚Äù is wrong. That erases all of the Jewish people who support Palestinian rights and the those that are opposed to Zionism. Judaism is a beautiful religion that is thousands of years old and Zionism is a political ideology that was born in middle of the 19th century. It also erases the long struggle of Palestinian Christians who make up more than 20% of the population. They are also dying in Gaza.¬†

The other thing I have to say is this, if you support Israel and you‚Äôre reading please know that I don‚Äôt hate you. I think you‚Äôre misguided but I can‚Äôt hate you. You‚Äôve been told lies, and one of the biggest lies you‚Äôve been told is that America can protect you. You‚Äôre being used.

The USA can buy you weapons and a shield but it can‚Äôt stop the rockets and missiles from coming. It offers no stability, there‚Äôs no road map to peace, think about it, it‚Äôs just Israel on the front line of WW3 like a crash test dummy! Iran, Syria, Lebanon, Pakistan, Saudi, Turkey, Iraq, Jordan etc‚Ä¶ the US has lost most of its influence and has no moral high ground left in the Middle East.¬†

This war has exposed many things. Not just the inhumanity of a 75 year occupation but it has proved that the world is watching and we won‚Äôt be lied to anymore.¬†

The situation in Palestine demands our unwavering attention and discussion. Above all, the loss of innocent lives on any side is deeply distressing and must be brought to an end. In times of conflict, it is often the civilians who suffer the most.

At present, Palestinian civilians find themselves trapped in the midst of the ongoing tensions between the militant group Hamas, which governs the territory, and Israeli forces. This unrest escalated when Hamas initiated a large-scale, attack on Israel. According to Palestinian authorities, over 1,055 individuals have tragically lost their lives, with another 5,184 sustaining injuries in Gaza due to Israeli retaliatory actions.

Hundreds of residences, including refugee camps, have been obliterated in the Gaza Strip, forcing over 123,000 people to flee their homes. To exacerbate the situation, Israel has imposed a comprehensive blockade on the already besieged Gaza Strip, even restricting access to essential supplies like food and water.

At the heart of this conflict lies the unlawful occupation of Palestinian territories, a clear violation of international law. Those enduring this illegal occupation possess a legitimate right to resist, and the occupier bears full legal responsibility. Israel's actions have significantly contributed to the current escalation, with the government using this crisis as a diversion from its domestic concerns.

Moreover, Israel's political stance has resulted in a dwindling comprehension of its policies in the Western world. Once again, Palestinians are being depicted as the primary aggressors, while the Israeli military, equipped with nuclear capabilities, portrays its actions as self-defense against perceived threats. Israel's leadership can rely on the unfortunate reality that many Western media outlets often fail to provide the necessary critical analysis, perpetuating a cycle of misunderstanding.

VAGUE MAGAZINE: As Australian newspapers provide readers with double page spreads explaining the complex history of the Gaza conflict this week, even the most unengaged voters have realised that the Indigenous Voice has not been given anywhere near the same focus.

The opportunity to keep Australians in the dark has been embraced by both the Nine Newspapers and NewsCorp, in effort to keep the waters as muddy as possible.

This intentionally vague coverage of a major moment in Australian history has only given rise to flat-earther levels of misinformation on social media, as Australians fall victim to conspiracy theories in their desperate search for answers.

Even the ABC have dedicated the vast majority of their referendum coverage to obsessively following the rollercoaster of Jacinta Price and Warren Mundine - two NO campaigners not well-known for discussing anything of substance.

In the final week of this misinformation vortex, a vast number of Australians are still asking 'Just tell me what the fuck this is?'

In short, the Indigenous Voice referendum is an opportunity for Australians to decide whether we include Indigenous people in our nation's passport-sized constitution - and provide them with a 'Voice To Parliament'

So basically, the Voice is a room in Parliament House for Indigenous elders and community leaders to convene ‚Äì and for politicians to visit if they have any questions they would like to ask about cultural protocol or unique experiences and circumstances.

Unfortunately, this information has not been readily available for any voters at any point throughout this campaign, for good reason, because our conservative media elites are terrified the Liberal Party might disappear if Peter Dutton doesn't land an easy win somewhere.

It's for this calculated lack of journalistic integrity, that one local Betoota grandmother is now learning about the Indigenous Voice through a grainy JPG of the Prime Minister dressed as a 1940s Soviet Dictator, complete with an Aboriginal flag manipulated to include a hammer and sickle - with block letters detailing completely illogical conspiracy theories riddled with spelling errors.

She never stood a chance.

Appeal: Urgent Support Needed For War Victims in Palestine

Donation Link Is In Highlights

We are reaching out to you today with a heartfelt appeal for your support and generosity. The ongoing conflict in Palestine has left countless innocent civilians, particularly women and children, in dire need of immediate assistance and humanitarian aid.

The situation has taken a devastating toll on the lives of people who have lost their loved ones, homes, and livelihoods. Hospitals and medical facilities are overwhelmed, struggling to cope with the increasing number of injured individuals who require urgent medical attention. The scarcity of basic necessities, such as food, clean water, and shelter, has plunged many into abject desperation.

In the face of such unimaginable suffering, we firmly believe in the power of collective action. Every amount, no matter how small, will make a significant impact in providing relief and rebuilding lives. Your support can help provide emergency medical supplies, food, water, and psychosocial support to those affected.

Together, we can assist humanitarian organizations on the ground who are working tirelessly to alleviate the suffering of war victims. Let us come together as a compassionate global community to extend a helping hand to our brothers and sisters in Palestine during this critical time.

Please consider making a generous contribution towards this cause. Your donation will provide solace and hope to those who have lost everything.

.
.
.
.

üåçüíî Standing in solidarity with the people of Israel and Palestine üíîüåç

In these challenging times, our hearts ache for the innocent lives affected by the recent bombings in Israel. We cannot turn a blind eye to the immense suffering and loss experienced by both Israelis and Palestinians. It is crucial to remember that every life lost is a tragedy, regardless of nationality or religion.

We believe in the power of compassion, empathy, and understanding. It is only through dialogue and peaceful coexistence that we can pave the way for a brighter future. Let us come together as a global community to support those affected by this devastating conflict.

We urge world leaders to prioritize diplomacy and seek a peaceful resolution that respects the rights and aspirations of both Israelis and Palestinians. It is essential to protect the lives of innocent civilians, especially children, who are the most vulnerable in times of conflict.

We stand with organizations and individuals working tirelessly on the ground to provide humanitarian aid, medical assistance, and support to those affected. Their efforts are invaluable, and we encourage everyone to contribute in any way they can.

Let us use our voices to spread awareness, promote understanding, and advocate for peace. Together, we can make a difference and help build a world where every person can live in safety, dignity, and harmony.

üì© Most of our fast and uncensored coverage of the conflict (with exclusive geopolitical analysis) will be in our daily email. Comment ‚ÄúJOIN‚Äù to get the updates and bypass the algorithm. These stories won‚Äôt be on Instagram.

‚ùì Question for you: Are you concerned that violence could erupt in America?

‚óè A little over a decade ago, a conflict in the Middle East showed the power of social media to keep global audiences informed about crises in real time. The way people used Facebook and Twitter during the uprisings known as the Arab Spring led to a surge of optimism about the important role these services could play for sharing information. Now another conflict in the Middle East is showing that the social media industry no longer sees that high-minded vision as part of its core mission.

‚óè In the hours after Hamas launched a large-scale attack on Israel over the weekend, people who turned to X, as Twitter is now known, were deluged with irrelevant or misleading reports, putting the consequences of Elon Musk‚Äôs loosening of content moderation rules on full display. Meta, meanwhile, has been very deliberately limiting the prominence of news and current events on services such as Facebook, Instagram and Threads.

‚óè The changes are a real issue for people who‚Äôve spent years relying on these social media platforms to understand what‚Äôs happening in the world.

Israel is at war. It has been over 48 hours since Palestinian terrorists from Hamas launched a widespread invasion of Southern Israel. We now know that October 7, 2023 was the deadliest day in Jewish history since the Holocaust. More than 800 Israelis have been killed since the attack began, and Israeli national security advisers believe the number of fatalities will rise to over 1000.

An additional 2500 have been wounded, and it‚Äôs believed that approximately 100 Israelis are being held prisoner by the Palestinian terrorists in Gaza. 9 Americans are among those killed, with an unknown number of Americans among the wounded and abducted. Hezbollah has threatened American troops throughout the Middle East should the United States enter this conflict.

Since the unprovoked attack, Israel has routed the terrorists from all farming communities and towns bordering the Gaza Strip. More than 300,000 Israeli reservists have been mobilized with indications that Israel is planning to extend its counterattack to a ground invasion of Gaza. This is the most rapid reservists call up in Israel‚Äôs history.

Presently, the Israelis have amassed at least 100,000 troops around the Gaza Strip, and have engaged in an aerial bombardment of the coastal region for nearly two days. Following exchanges of artillery fire just this morning, Hezbollah terrorists infiltrated Northern Israel. Following reports that Iran was behind the October 7th Massacre, Jerusalem has also mobilized significant numbers of troops along its Syrian and Lebanese borders, should the Iran-backed terrorist army decide to open up a second front against the Jewish state.

I want to be clear, Israel will do whatever it deems necessary to protect its people, and we will vigorously stand with Israel. The world is different today than it was before this weekend‚Äôs massacre. No longer is the distinction between good and evil so easily blurred by Anti-Israel sympathizers in the media. A very clear line has been drawn in the sand, and everyone, both individuals and nations, must choose between Israel and the madness of terrorism.

Aaron and Tamar Greene were preparing for one of the most special days of their lives, their wedding day, when bombs began to rock Israel, where they both live.

Tamar Greene recalled that at the time the attack started, she and Aaron were separated from each other, following tradition of the bride and groom not seeing each other the week before the wedding.

"We just had to cancel everything, cancel all the celebrations, and were constantly running back and forth into the bomb shelter."

The start of the conflict was especially worrisome for the couple because Aaron Greene is also a reservist with the Israel Defense Forces. Aaron Greene, a paratrooper, said he first watched as his friends got called into duty, and then received the call to serve himself.

Read more at our link in bio.

Israeli troops are massing for what‚Äôs widely seen as all but inevitable: a ground invasion of Gaza.

The public and the national security establishment in Israel are demanding retribution for the attacks by Hamas militants that claimed more than 1,000 Israeli lives over the weekend. But a ground invasion would be complicated by Gaza‚Äôs dense population, its complex underground network of tunnels and the danger it would pose to Israelis, Americans and others being held hostage.

An invasion would bring heavy casualties on both sides and questions about whether Israel can devise an exit strategy for the conflict. It would also create ripple effects through the Middle East, increasing the risks that the conflict spirals into a broader regional war. Tap the link in our bio for analysis of how such an operation would play out.

#IsraelPalestineWar | The death toll in the ongoing Israel-Hamas conflict has crossed 2,100 with the majority of the fatalities being on the Israeli side from the surprise attack of the militia on Saturday.

According to Israeli media, the death toll crossed 1,200 on Tuesday with close to 3,000 injured and the fate of an estimated 150 people abducted and taken to the Gaza Strip still unclear.

The death toll hit a grim 1,000 late Tuesday and the number climbed to 1,200 by Wednesday morning. The Health Ministry in the Hamas-run coastal enclave has claimed that the total number of deaths due to Israeli attacks on the Gaza Strip reached 900, while 4,500 others were injured, including 15 paramedics and 20 journalists.

It also said the fatalities include 260 children and 230 women, as well as 22 families who were killed in their entirety. On Tuesday, the IDF had claimed that it had recovered around bodies of around 1,500 Hamas gunmen who had infiltrated into Israeli territory.

Meanwhile, Israel which declared war on Saturday continued with its aerial attacks across Gaza, turning parts of the Hamas-controlled area into a pile of rubble.

The worst hit has been Gaza City's upscale Rimal neighborhood, which is home to shopping malls, restaurants, residential buildings, offices and home to Hamas government ministries.

The Israeli military's Arabic spokesperson, Avichay Adraee, said that Israel was trying to ‚Äúevacuate civilian populations from areas where Hamas has a military presence‚Äù before unleashing ‚Äúpowerful destruction," which Gaza residents say is untrue. 

Israeli Defence Minister Yoav Gallant on Tuesday said the IDF is moving to "full offence" against Hamas targets.

"I have released all the restraints. We have [regained] control of the area and we are moving to a full offence," he said in an address to troops deployed along the Gaza border.

Meanwhile, the aircraft carrying US arms to Israel has reportedly landed in the country. The IDF did not specify what kind of armaments or equipment it got from the US, which had reaffirmed its support for Israel and the country's right to defend itself.

Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and former Defense Minister Benny Gantz have formed a temporary unity government and war-time cabinet to focus on the fight ahead with Hamas. 

The new emergency government brings two opposition leaders - both former Army leaders - and greater military know-how into the decision making process.  Proponents hope the temporary alliance will add legitimacy to the leadership‚Äôs choices.

Among the decisions they confront: will Israel send ground troops into Gaza to attempt to rescue hostages? Or is this a trap that will only lead to more slaughter and suffering and escalate the war? They‚Äôll also confront the challenges posed by increased fighting with Hezbollah to the North and the possibility of armed conflict from the West Bank and even Syria.

The emergency wartime government will focus only on decisions related to the conflict. 

Netanyahu has agreed that he will not pursue highly controversial domestic ‚Äújudicial reforms‚Äù while the war is ongoing. All year Israel has been been rocked by protests against the policies of Netanyahu‚Äôs unpopular far right government. 

To our American audience and those not familiar: Israel has a parliamentary system with more than two dominant political parties. Israeli politicians are experienced in governing together. They are now choosing a ‚Äúpower sharing‚Äù arrangement. Think of this as broadly akin to Democrats and Republicans sharing government power and making decisions about war together.

The Russian leader made the comments while meeting Iraq‚Äôs Prime Minister Mohammed Shia Al-Sudani in Moscow, days after Hamas launched a massive attack on Israel.

‚ÄúI think many people would agree with me that it‚Äôs a clear example of the failure of US politics in the Middle East,‚Äù Putin said.

He spoke of the ‚Äúnecessity to implement the decisions of the UN Security Council on the creation of an independent sovereign Palestinian state.‚Äù

Putin said the US had ‚Äútried to monopolize regulating (the conflict) but, unfortunately, were not preoccupied with looking for compromises that would be acceptable for both sides.‚Äù

Finding the calm within the chaos ‚ú®

We all prefer when things are working in a favour, but on essential part of life mastery is learning to ride the storm is staying calm and anchored amidst the chaos. When life disrupts our peace of mind and presents us with challenges, as it inevitably will, there is always a tendency to turn our backs in resistance. Fear, pain, loss and grief or unpleasant trees that nobody wants to feel, so rather than face the stress and anxiety play my calls, we often push them away in the hopes they will disappear. The problem is that when we resist, we come into conflict with our present moment reality and we actually give these feelings power.

The road to peace as such begins when we can face these feelings, allowing them to rise and fall, to come and go, or without the need to control. If we can approach them, even in the most difficult of circumstances, with a willingness to be with our experience, in total acceptance of what is, we open a possibility of landing peacefully in the present moment of our lives. In other words, we must continue to weave with patients and resilience trusting in the bigger picture. 

ü´∂

There's a heaviness in knowing that so many people are suffering in unimaginable ways. There's a heaviness in understanding that conflict like this never spares children, on either side. There's a heaviness in my 10 year old asking "Mummy why is there another war?" There's a heaviness recognising that, despite the heaviness, life here carries on but that elsewhere it quite literally does not. My thoughts, and my heart, are with everyone impacted. Trite, but true.

Imagine a world where one in five girls does not have access to a quality education.

This isn't a dystopian novel. This is reality.

Across the globe, twenty percent of girls are denied the basic right to learn, to grow, to dream.

In developing countries, two-thirds of illiterate youth are girls. Two-thirds. Picture the dreams that go unfulfilled, the potential that goes untapped, simply because they lack the opportunity to read and write.

In conflict zones, girls are two and a half times more likely to be out of school than boys.

The bullet of war doesn't only shatter homes; it shatters futures.

It shatters the dreams of girls who could become scientists, artists, leaders.

But the story doesn't end there. It's not just about the statistics. It's about the spirit. The spirit of every girl who has ever dared to dream.

Despite these odds, girls around the world are standing up, speaking out, and sparking change.

They are becoming the first in their families to graduate high school or college.

They are leading their communities towards a brighter future.

They are proving that when you invest in a girl's education, you invest in a nation's future.

The world is full of girls with dreams as vast as the sky and potential as deep as the ocean.

They are not just statistics.

They are stories of resilience, of hope, of power.

They are the promise of a brighter tomorrow.

So today, on this International Day of the Girl, remember this: Every girl holds the power to shape the world. Every girl is a beacon of hope. Every girl is a testament to the indomitable spirit of humankind.

Because every girl, no matter where she comes from, no matter what circumstances she is born into, has the potential to rise. To soar. To shatter the glass ceilings that have been placed above her.

Every girl has the power to change the world. And that is a story worth telling.

MATW has been on the ground working in Palestine and Gaza providing emergency relief and rebuilding homes. 

Our MATW team works tirelessly to ensure humanitarian aid is delivered to those who are most vulnerable including women, children and the elderly. 

We work closely with local suppliers in Palestine ensuring essentials such as *food items, meals, medical kits, mattresses, blankets and more* are secured and maintained so that our teams are constantly ready to deliver aid - especially in times of crisis when the cost of these items are inflated, making them beyond reach for those we serve. 

The blockade further inflates prices in the region, hence the rising costs of living for locals affected, and the need for able brothers and sisters (our generous donors) to contribute to ensure the delivery of these basic necessities.

Dehumanization is the negating of a person's individual humanity and the cruelty that accompanies it. It‚Äôs a psychological process of demonizing people, seeing them as less than human and, hence, not worthy of humane treatment.

This method reverses our instincts: harming others goes against our soul-level inclinations as there are very deep inhibitions that prevent us from treating others like sub-human; dehumanization is aimed at subverting those inhibitions.

Throughout history, this technique has been deliberately exploited by structures of darkness to distract, sow division, push concealed agendas, increase power and justify acts of violence, slavery, and the violation of basic human rights. When successful, it creates moral exclusion of groups that are targeted based on their identity‚Äîe.g., religious beliefs, nationality, gender, race, ethnicity, medical status‚Äîand depicted as ‚Äúless than,‚Äù criminal or even evil. 

The ‚Äúothering‚Äù scheme always starts with identifying an enemy and creating an ‚Äúus vs. them‚Äù dynamic, where innocent people become pawns and victims. As we take sides, lose trust, and get angrier and angrier, we not only solidify an idea of the other as separate, but also start to lose our ability to listen, communicate, and even practice the slightest of empathy. Language and imagery are crucial for achieving the dehumanizing goal (e.g., in Rwanda, Hutus called Tutsis cockroaches). Once we see people ‚Äúon the other side‚Äù as morally inferior and even dangerous, the conflict is then framed as good versus evil. When this framework has been established, positions become more rigid as we are lead to believe that we must either destroy ‚Äúothers‚Äù or be destroyed ourselves. The dehumanizing aim has then been achieved.

Now more than ever we need to acknowledge that we‚Äôre all vulnerable to the slow, insidious and manipulative psychological weapon of dehumanization. Only by acknowledging this and searching for compassion and healing within our hearts we can avoid falling into this trap and prevent history from repeating itself in a never-ending cycle of darkness.

War dehumanizes. And dehumanization leads to war. We will never normalize any of the two.

Edik walked 12 miles to stop and fill up his fuel cans before leaving Nagorno-Karabakh. But in a horrific explosion at the gas station, hundreds of Armenians were burned, including Edik.

The blast had left Edik with burns over 40 percent of his body and with deep burn wounds to his face, back, and limbs. His legs and hands took the brunt.

While trying to get back to his family, he fought the almost-constant urge to give in to the shock his body was experiencing as it reacted to the life-threatening injuries. 

Edik along with more than 100,000 ethnic Armenians have fled Nagorno-Karabakh since this latest escalation of conflict. In response to the great needs, our team has airlifted 30+ tons of relief supplies and sent burn specialists to help meet critical needs as we work alongside local church partners and hospitals.

‚ÄúThe depth and extent of these are probably some of the worst I‚Äôve seen in my 27 years of experience working in burn treatment. The amount of suffering here is beyond human comprehension,‚Äù said Joany, a nurse on our Disaster Assistance Response Team (DART).

Since the beginning of our response, our specialists have treated several dozen burn victims with wound care and skin grafts, and, in the most severe cases, with post-operative physical therapy.

Jessica uses her physical therapy skills to strategically mobilize patients to help strengthen their bodies and prevent further injuries. For some, that means sitting up on their own. For others, it is learning to walk again.

In the few days that Edik has worked with Jessica, his outlook has brightened. Even as tears streamed down one cheek, he began to smile. 

‚ÄúTwo days ago, I was so depressed that I thought I would never come out of this hospital,‚Äù he said. ‚ÄúBut because of Jessica, I have hope. Her positivity brought a lot of change in this hospital. I‚Äôm very grateful for her. When she comes here, it gives us hope.‚Äù

On Saturday morning, Hamas troops carried out a planned attack on Israel, first firing rockets into the country and then carrying out attacks by land, sea and air, according to the New York Times. The attack infiltrated 22 cities in Israel and by Sunday morning, officials reported 700 Israelis as dead after the attacks, with an estimated 150 other civilians and soldiers held hostage.

Israel formally declared war against Hamas on Sunday and carried out an air attack on the Gaza Strip neighborhood Tuesday morning. The war has claimed the lives of soldiers and civilians on both sides and is the result of over two-centuries of conflict.

I am opposed to plans for a blanket ban on Palestinian Australians gathering in NSW in support of their people. The civilian suffering in the conflict is universal, and we should not have the right to deny Australians the ability to peacefully assemble.

Leaders within the Palestinian community, including religious institutions, need to come out strongly to rebuke calls for violence and condemn the slaughter of innocent civilians by Hamas. The government and police need to work with organizers to prevent the celebration of terrorism against civilians and take direct action against any incitement to violence. Any display of support for terrorism must be dealt with swiftly.

If organizers are unable to do this and are not confident that their presence may not further inflame the situation, they should take matters into their own hands to minimize the damage this will do to their cause publicly in Australia. It is their responsibility, and the rest of the country has every right to judge their actions on the day.

If the ban stays in place and a protest led by the same organizers goes ahead and we see the same scenes as the other night in front of the Opera House but this time with clashes with police, the damage to the perception of Palestinian people in Australia will be immense. 

Australians should always have every right to oppose war and advocate for peace. At times like this, it can be uncomfortable to be principled, but that is what sets us apart from much of the turmoil around the world.

I'm going to share an experience that occurred while I was up on the mauna on Indigenous Peoples Day.  Please do not reshare it. As I was driving up, I was pondering about the war that just broke out and thinking about how little I know about either Israel or Palestine or the Gaza Strip except for what I see on social media or what I've seen on Netflix's Fauda. After I gave my offering and was walking back to my car, a woman came up to me and asked if she could go up to the ahu as she wanted to pray for her family in Israel as they had already lost loved ones in the first day and I could see her sadness. I said to her that I'd go up with her and we could pray together for both sides and all of the victims, the families, the people. I expressed to her that the social media from Hawai'i I see is pro Palestinian because of occupation and all she asked me was if I could please learn more, do my research, that the people are good people and I agreed that I would so I'm starting with Who exactly is Hamas because I just watched World News and a Palestinian in Gaza says they themselves have been kept hostage by Hamas all these years and the attacks on Israel have nothing to do with the people and they are dying now as well. This is not a post for any of you to comment on, Im not exacting an opinion, and I'll be doing a lot of reading and watching. I'm just saying that I don't know anything about their history or long standing conflict and I need to learn more, but what I do know is war equals death every time and I'll just be praying for those suffering right now no matter what side they're on. Thankful for the chance encounter which really wasn't a chance meeting after all but instead a teaching moment for me. It just reminds me of how far away from this we live. I'll delete this post if those reading it just skim and give me negative comments. I just wanted to share how little I know and how much I have to learn, that's all. I write with love in my heart.

What I‚Äôve done this week is consistent with what I‚Äôve done for almost a decade now. 

As a proponent of nonviolence, there were several actions in the heyday of the BLM-era I didn‚Äôt align with (though 97% of demonstrations were nonviolent). I didn‚Äôt take to the internet to tell you where *I* stand because that‚Äôs not what‚Äôs most important to me. It has no bearing on the material conditions of the conflict situation.

I also didn‚Äôt believe that the worst elements of Black resistance characterized the struggle as a whole; if anything, they did point to the severity of the oppression they addressed and the desperation of my people to be free.

Instead of denouncing or condoning ‚Äî again, things that have no meaning from someone like me ‚Äî I tried to offer context, even when people performed actions I thought were ill-advised, unstrategic, or just plain wrong. I also used those as opportunities to confront bad but popular assumptions about social change, from my research.

It isn‚Äôt just recent movements I‚Äôve had to view like this. I have to tell you, I wince at Fanon‚Äôs accounts of decolonial struggles. I want him to be wrong when he says ‚ÄúDecolonization‚Ä¶is clearly an agenda for social disorder.‚Äù I don‚Äôt have much of a stomach to read about slave rebellions where they indiscriminately killed their oppressors and anyone who looked like their oppressors (yes, including women and children). They are things I‚Äôve had to accept as realities of the dynamics and possibilities of armed struggle for freedom. 

To be abundantly clear: I didn‚Äôt respond with this info because innocents were killed in the news. I responded this way because some of you said ‚ÄúThis doesn‚Äôt happen when people are decolonizing.‚Äù But it does happen. It‚Äôs not a justification to state a fact. 

These are not ideals I profess or actions I would perform myself. But I can‚Äôt ignore or erase them. 

As someone interested in freedom, I think it‚Äôs my duty to understand them.

I have the same attitude now.

I don‚Äôt feel the capacity or privilege for moral pronouncements. I‚Äôm  here to point out where we‚Äôre making assumptions and proclamations about change that aren‚Äôt supported by history or the data I know.

The destruction in the last few days, the families broken and homes bombed has to be a wake up call. 

Palestinians have lived under occupation, under these conditions, for decades. Can we acknowledge their continual plight for freedom? For human rights?

Thousands of Israelis have been bullied and beaten for standing shoulder to shoulder with their Palestinian brothers and sisters. 

The brave will never be silenced. 

Media & Politicians in the Middle East, Europe and the US have blood on their hands. The enablers have destroyed a land sacred to all. 

Wherever you stand on the Israeli/Palestinian conflict, please, have compassion, always. Only a freak, a psychopath, will get any pleasure seeing a father pleading for the release of his child or a father whispering in the ear of the dead daughter he carries in his arms. 

These images don‚Äôt belong in the 21st Century. 

This is not us. 
We are better than this.
We can do better than this.

The Thangjam family made a decision that would light up their world in white. At first, they were hesitant about the proposal for a photoshoot, unsure of what would happen. However, they soon embraced it wholeheartedly.

Amos Thangjam's wife, Nisana, an expectant mother at eight months, shared her thoughts:
"I'm always at home, and I really wish I could be out there, taking part in this movement. But given my condition, it's not possible. We're grateful for this chance to capture our family moments and donate something to help the victims."

The eldest son in the family, Kenon, couldn't hide his excitement:
"I'm delighted to experience the whole process," he said with a beaming smile. "It feels good knowing that we're making a difference. What's more, we have a special photo of our parents together, something we've wished for a long time. We wish the Epic team all the best."

Pabung Keshorjit, the patriarch of the family, expressed his deep sorrow for the conflict victims and the beloved state of Manipur:
"It's heart-wrenching to know that we can't do much to help," he said, his voice filled with emotion. "But we're happy that we can at least contribute through this initiative. I pray to God that everything gets better soon, and peace prevails in our beloved Manipur."

And so, dressed in white as a symbol of unity, the Thangjam family embarked on a journey of hope, compassion, and support for the relief fund. Together, they stand strong, believing that even the smallest efforts can create a big impact.

---
