The promises of war never justify its true costs.
========
Living in a melting pot like California, where diversity is its essence, I am privileged to have friends from varied backgrounds, including Israeli and Palestinian roots. As news flashes images of devastating acts against innocent lives in the conflict in the Middle East, my heart wrenches in pain. These images resonate profoundly with me, not merely as abstract tragedies but as palpable echoes of my own heritage. As the son of a Vietnamese refugee, I am all too familiar with the scars left behind by wars that bifurcate families and communities over ideological differences. Through myriad conversations with veterans of the Vietnamese War, both American and Vietnamese, a haunting consensus emerges when asked, 'Was it worth the fight?'. The answer, invariably and poignantly, is ‚ÄòNO‚Äô.‚Äù

At most of AHS' major centres, the Protective Services teams are made up of AHS Peace Officers, contracted Security Guards, and Safety Ambassadors. 

The ‚ÄúC Team‚Äù at Rockyview General Hospital (RGH) consists of Security Guard Mia Russell (left), Peace Officers Joel Alex, Vishal Mittu, and Gurvir Gill, Safety Ambassador Kenzie Fraser, and their Team Lead Aaron Travnicek (not pictured). Victoria Liu (right) is a Calgary Rural Mobile Unit Peace Officer who travels to different healthcare sites across the zone.

‚ÄúWhen you walk into a hospital, our people are often the first point of engagement,‚Äù says Jay Sortland, Protective Services Site Manager at RGH. 

‚ÄúFrom Safety Ambassadors ‚Äì non-uniformed team members who conduct safety checks, consult with hospital staff, identify potential risks and perform initial de-escalation of conflict ‚Äì to Peace Officers and contracted Security Guards, we play a direct role in the delivery of patient care.‚Äù

Sortland explains that each team member brings a diverse perspective and set of skills to help provide safer and more secure spaces for patients, families and staff.

Conflict in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC; the Congo) has been ongoing since the 1990s. The country has faced political repression and instability since it achieved independence in 1960. DRC is the fourth largest African country by population and the most populous francophone country in the world, and is home to an abundance of vital natural resources. 

Currently, eastern DRC is the site of ethnic conflict and violent resource competition involving ethnic militias, Congolese security forces, UN troops, and complex external interests. 

The abundance of natural resources (precious minerals) found in Congolese soil has globalized the conflict in eastern DRC. While U.S. companies once owned vast cobalt mines in the Congo, most were sold to Chinese companies during the Barack Obama and Donald Trump administrations. 

Chinese companies connected to Beijing now control the MAJORITY of foreign owned cobalt, uranium, and copper mines in DRC and the Congolese army has been repeatedly deployed to mining sites in eastern DRC to PROTECT CHINESE ASSETS. 

In 2023, DRC is home to an estimated 5.7 million internally displaced people in urgent need of more than 2 billion dollars in medical and other aid. Nearly a million Congolese nationals are seeking refuge in other African states. Exacerbating this need for assistance, the UN has suspended air deliveries of aid to certain eastern provinces.

Casualties remain on the rise as armed groups attack displacement camps, civilians in the DRC and abroad, and self-defense groups. In May, the South African Development Community (SADC) agreed to deploy troops to eastern Congo to assist UN forces ahead of the December 2023 elections. However, a month later the UN announced a planned withdrawal of the largely unpopular MOUSCO peacekeeping mission, a decision the United States called premature.

Dear SBCC Community, 

Our hearts are heavy in understanding the realities of the violent acts in Israel over the weekend. Innocent civilians, including children and elderly, have lost their lives or are wounded, and many others have been taken hostage. This act of terrorism occurred on a major Jewish holiday, and we stand against this unfathomable event. 

Currently, Israeli cities are under attack, and warfare continues in Gaza, with more innocent lives affected. These actions deeply sadden us. Though this conflict may be geographically distant, SBCC recognizes its impact affects many locally and humanity everywhere. 

We want to remind our community that SBCC is a place where we value belonging, compassion, and kindness. We stand ready to offer support and resources to our students, faculty, and staff affected by these tragic events.

For students: SBCC‚Äôs Student Health & Wellness
Phone: (805) 730-4098
Visit Offices: SS-170 - Student Services Building, first floor room 170
Office hours:
Mon-Thu: 9 a.m - 4 p.m. (in person & remote)
Fri: 9 a.m. - 1 p.m. (remote services only)

For employees: SBCC‚Äôs Employee Assistance Program
Call (800) 999-7222 or visit anthemEAP.com and enter SISC for the company code. 
Self-Insured Schools of CA Employee Assistance Program (SISC EAP) is available to ALL SBCC employees, dependents and anyone living in your immediate household. 
The program provides confidential counseling and referral services for job-related or personal challenges.
Up to 6 counseling sessions are provided per benefit year and are covered at no cost. 

It is with great hope that we come together with kindness, empathy, and love to support those in the SBCC community and our surrounding area who are grieving and experiencing anxiety due to this violence. May we find peace and heal. 

Erika Endrijonas, Ph.D.

COLOMBO (News 1st); The Sri Lanka Foreign Employment Bureau has reached a decision to send Sri Lankans to work in Israel only after obtaining the necessary approvals from the Population and Immigration Authority in Israel, the Sri Lanka Embassy in Israel and the Ministry of Foreign Affairs.

Deputy General Manager Gamini Senarath Yapa said the decision was reached taking into consideration the uncertainty caused by the Israeli-Palestinian conflict.

He said Sri Lankan workers are sent to Israel based on a Memorandum of Understanding signed between the two countries.

Sri Lankan Ambassador to Israel Nimal Bandara said if Sri Lankan workers want to leave Israel, they have the opportunity to do so.

He said three flights operate from Israel to Colombo daily, via Dubai, Abu Dhabi and Bahrain.

In a time marked by tension and conflict, the media's role in providing accurate, responsible news coverage becomes even more crucial. A recent incident involving #CNN has raised eyebrows and sparked criticism, as netizens allege the news network of faking an attack on Israeli Occupation.

The controversy centers around a video clip aired by CNN, which depicts an attack in the Israeli Occupation, where rockets are heard. However, what ignited the furor was the voiceover accompanying the video. Critics argue that the voiceover, which carried a British accent, appeared artificial and detached from the original event.

The backlash against CNN primarily revolves around the voiceover's alleged lack of authenticity. Social media users scrutinized the video, asserting that the voiceover sounded pre-recorded and not in sync with the actual events on the ground. This perception has fueled skepticism about the credibility of CNN's reporting.

An Indian political analyst Zaid Khan posted a video on X, formerly Twitter, of CNN's report. He wrote: "CNN EXPOSED FOR FAKING AN ATTACK IN ISRAEL."

A social media user replied to his tweet: "The voice was added over the original soundtrack and is obviously fake. It's terrible that this war is happening, but it's truly diabolical that someone would make light of it. This is not a joke."

Another replied: "Why CNN journalists was speaking with British accent?"

One wrote: "Voiceover is fake as confirmed by the video original author."

Are you stuck in a friendship maze, wondering if it‚Äôs time to make a great escape from your current friend group? It‚Äôs a dilemma many of us face at some point in our lives. Friends come and go, but sometimes, it‚Äôs necessary to revisit the dynamics of your social circle. So, how can you tell if it‚Äôs time to pack your bags and leave the friend group behind?

Take a moment to reflect on how you feel when you‚Äôre with your friends. Are you genuinely happy, or do you find yourself constantly drained or anxious? Friends should uplift your spirits, not drain your energy.

Consider your interests and values. Have they evolved, leaving you with little in common with your current friends? It‚Äôs okay to outgrow people, as personal growth is a beautiful part of life. Friends who make you feel excluded and judged are the ones you should part ways with. 

Conflict is another red flag. If you constantly feel misunderstood or unheard in arguments, that could be a sign to just drop the whole argument and walk away. Healthy friendships involve open communication and mutual respect.

Don‚Äôt disregard toxic behaviors either. If your friends are engaging in destructive habits that you can‚Äôt condone, it‚Äôs perfectly fine to distance yourself from those influences.

Always trust your instincts. If your gut feeling is telling you it‚Äôs time to leave, it probably is. Your intuition knows what‚Äôs best for you.

Esther (1875)
By
Hugues Merle (1823-1881)

"Esther" by Hugues Merle is a masterful representation of Academic style in the art world during the late 19th century. Merle, often likened to his contemporary William Bouguereau, is known for his meticulous attention to detail, and in this particular painting, he draws inspiration from mythology, literature, and religion. The subject of this work is Esther, the celebrated heroine of the Old Testament.

In this captivating piece, Esther's internal turmoil and her courageous decision take center stage. Her eyes convey a profound sense of inner conflict as she grapples with the life-altering choice of breaking court etiquette to intercede for the Jewish people before her husband, King Ahasuerus of Persia. This painting is not only a testament to Merle's artistic skill but also a portrayal of the psychological depth of his subjects.

Esther is surrounded by King Ahasuerus and an attendant, further emphasizing the tension and importance of the narrative. Merle's ability to capture the emotional complexity of the characters in this biblical story is a testament to his talent as an artist.

As one who was born and raised Muslim and now is a follower of Jesus. As one who has lived through a war in which Saddam Hussein invaded Kuwait. As one who faced discrimination after 9/11. As one who can only imagine the horror of what is going on. 

Here are my thoughts: 

We have to resist the temptation to simplify and categorize this into either a pro-Israel or pro-Palestine conflict. This is a pro-humanity conversation. 

Standing with one people group is problematic. In this case there are decades of conflict and injustice on both sides. When you stand with one people group, you automatically discriminate against the other. We subconsciously give ourselves permission to be cruel to a certain people group simply because they belong to that group or are associated with them. We can easily justify distrust, disdain and unloving actions, because we have categorized a certain people group. We need to cry out and seek justice for people regardless if they're Palestinian or they are Israeli. We need to mourn with people wherever they are. Our hearts need to break for loved ones that are being tortured, held hostage and being killed, regardless of their race. We have to stand with each other as one humanity against evil.

Stand against evil. We should not tolerate evil. Evil is so insidious because it wants to fester in the human heart. Evil knows that if we are focused on a certain people group, we will not pay attention to the evil we've allowed to operate in our own lives. The problem has always been evil. Regardless of where it lies - either in an Israeli heart, or a Palestinian heart - it needs to be eradicated. People who've allowed evil to take over their lives should not be allowed to affect innocent lives. 

Stand for justice, not revenge. After 9/11, when terrorists devastated us by their attacks, we went not only after justice, but revenge, and launched ourselves into decades of war. It also gave evil people an excuse to commit hate crimes against particular people groups‚Ä¶

Operation Pawan was a military operation conducted by the Indian Peace Keeping Force (IPKF) in Sri Lanka. It took place between July 11, 1987, and March 24, 1990. The operation was aimed at stabilizing the situation in Sri Lanka during a period of civil conflict. The civil conflict in Sri Lanka stemmed from the demands of the Tamil ethnic minority for greater autonomy and equal rights. The Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE), a militant organization, led the armed struggle for Tamil independence. The situation deteriorated, leading to violence and instability in the country. The Indian government, led by Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi, decided to intervene in Sri Lanka to address the deteriorating situation. Operation Pawan involved the deployment of the IPKF, comprising Indian Army and paramilitary forces, to Sri Lanka. Its primary objectives were to disarm the LTTE, maintain peace, and facilitate a political solution to the conflict. Operation Pawan faced several challenges, including resistance from the LTTE, and the situation escalated into a full-scale military conflict. The operation had a significant human and economic cost for India. Despite initial successes, the IPKF's presence and actions faced resistance and opposition from various Tamil militant groups. The operation also resulted in strained relations between India and Sri Lanka. Ultimately, Operation Pawan did not fully achieve its objectives. The IPKF withdrew from Sri Lanka in 1990 without having fully disarmed the LTTE, and the conflict continued for many more years. The operation highlighted the complexities of military intervention in a foreign country's internal conflict and the challenges of achieving a lasting peace settlement. The Sri Lankan civil conflict persisted for nearly three more decades, ending in 2009 with the defeat of the LTTE. #operationpawan #theforgottenwar #talkdiplomacy #upsc #css #upscmotivation #upscaspirants #csstricks #srilanka #ipkf #indianpeacekeepingforce #liberationtigersoftamileelam #rajivgandhi #internationalrelations #internationalrelationsstudent #tamil #1

Today, my heart is heavy as I contemplate the ongoing war in Israel. It is a conflict riddled with senseless killing and unimaginable acts of violence. The innocent lives lost, the women and children taken away from their families‚Äîit is a tragedy that shakes us to our core. 

In the midst of this chaos, it is difficult to comprehend the motivations of those who perpetrate such heinous acts. How can anyone justify the intentional harm inflicted upon the most vulnerable members of society? It is a cowardly and despicable act, one that defies the very essence of humanity.

Religion, meant to be a source of solace, guidance, and love, has become a battleground for divisiveness and hatred. People have lost sight of the core teachings that advocate compassion, understanding, and respect for one another. We have allowed our own beliefs to blind us, to turn us into agents of destruction rather than forces of healing.

God, in any faith tradition, teaches us love. It is a universal message that transcends borders, cultures, and religions. Love is the foundation upon which true peace is built. Yet, in the midst of this turmoil, love seems to be overshadowed by fear, anger, and vengeance.

For those of us fortunate enough to live in more stable regions, let us pause before we complain about the trivialities of our daily lives. We are blessed with safety, security, and opportunities that many others can only dream of. Our complaints pale in comparison to the harrowing reality faced by those living in war-torn areas.

As we witness the destruction and devastation unfolding before our eyes, it becomes increasingly difficult to find the right words to express our sorrow. The fear and pain endured by the innocent victims are unimaginable to those of us watching from afar. It is a pain that pierces the soul and leaves us searching for answers.

In times like these, we must unite in our shared humanity. Regardless of our faith, ethnicity, or nationality, we must stand together against the forces of evil that seek to divide us. We must raise our voices for peace, advocate for justice, and work tirelessly to create a world where every life is valued and cherished.

I grieve feeling safe working on her. It is clear by how the break in occurred it was thought through-  someone came with the right tools and at the right time- Leaving me with the unnerving question was I being watched?

Kuwait's Minister of Foreign Affairs Sheikh Salem Abdullah Al-Jaber Al-Sabah reiterated strong condemnation of the inhuman practices committed by the Zionist occupation authorities against the Palestinian people. On 2nd November 1917, a public statement issued by the British government in 1917 during the First World War kicked off over 100 years of confusion, conflict and all-out war. This is the Balfour Declaration.

Written three years into Britain's declaration of war on the Ottoman Empire by the United Kingdom's Foreign Secretary Arthur Balfour and addressed to Lord Rotschild, a leader of the British Jewish community, the statement announced its support for the establishment of a "national home for the Jewish people" in Palestine, which was back then an Ottoman region with a small minority Jewish population. One week later, the statement was published in the press... and the rest is a long and blurry history.

Fast forward three decades and two world wars, and Britain passed on "the Palestine problem" to the United Nations in early 1947. "We have tried for years to solve the problem," a representative told the UN. "We now bring it to the United Nations in the hope that it can succeed where we have not."

One year and a redrawing of the region's new borders later, Zionist military forces expelled at least 750,000 Palestinians and captured 78% of historic Palestine. The remaining 22% was divided into the West Bank and the Gaza Strip, two of the world's most contested and conflict-heavy territories in recent history.

Fast forward seven and a half more decades of conflict, and this weekend saw an escalation which has devolved into an all-out war between Israel and Hamas. Barrages of rockets are being fired from both sides, and hundreds of civilians and citizens continue to be found dead with every passing day.

Of course, this long-standing territorial dispute is much more nuanced and goes way beyond simple letters and maps, but that one statement written all the way back in 1917 is often seen as the catalyst for over 100 years of pain and suffering in the region.

Had you ever heard of the Balfour Declaration? Send this to someone who needs to check this out.

Hamilcar Barca, often celebrated as the father of the renowned Hannibal, assumed the challenging role of leading Carthaginian forces in an effort to regain territory lost to Rome in Sicily. As discussed earlier, the strategically vital city of Agrigentum had been captured by Rome.

Hamilcar's campaigns in Sicily began with promise. His forces secured a series of victories against the Romans, resulting in significant territorial gains on the island. Hamilcar's strategic genius and adaptability on the battlefield played a pivotal role in these early successes.

However, as the conflict continued, Hamilcar encountered logistical and strategic obstacles. Maintaining his forces in Sicily proved to be challenging due to Carthage's limited resources and the difficulty of providing adequate support. These constraints hampered his ability to conduct further offensive operations.

The Romans were formidable adversaries as their adaptability to Carthaginian tactics and strategies presented an ongoing challenge to Hamilcar. The Roman navy, in particular, posed a significant hurdle.

Nevertheless, in the face of these challenges, Hamilcar demonstrated remarkable tactical brilliance. His ability to secure victories and capture strategic positions highlighted his military prowess. His adeptness at choosing advantageous terrain and using it to his advantage in battle was a standout feature of his campaigns.

Hamilcar Barca's campaigns in Sicily, characterized by a mix of successes and obstacles, left a lasting legacy. They laid the foundation for Carthaginian military endeavors that followed and etched a memorable chapter in history. These lessons would be inherited by Hamilcar's son, Hannibal Barca, who would refine them in his renowned campaigns during the Second Punic War.

APCLS rebels on the march, outside of Kitchanga, 2022. 

Fighting is currently ongoing across North Kivu as a counter-offensive is launched against M23 rebels. Mai-Mai and Nyatura militias, under the banner of the ‚Äòpatriotic self-defense‚Äô forces, are on the march, occupying much of Masisi territory. 

Eastern Congo is home to over 120 armed groups, with the Kivu provinces torn apart by these rebel fiefdoms. 

Many of these groups were re-mobilised at the end of 2022 as the Congolese army forgave former enemies in the hope of galvanising support and slowing the rapid advance of M23 across the province. Good Rebels versus Bad Rebels. 

Yet, more used to banditry against civilians than sustained combat, these militias were swept aside by M23 units which nearly succeeded in isolating the city of Goma. 

In the town of Kitchanga, shortly before it fell to M23 in January 2023, I met General Janvier as he was mustering his APCLS Mai Mai combattants. 

Through the years, the town has had a macabre history of occupations and counterattacks. In 2018, on my very first commission in Eastern Congo, I was sent there to photograph demobilised child soldiers, recovering from deeply traumatising experiences. 5 years on, and as Kitchanga changes hands for the 3rd time so far in the conflict, it is clear that impunity reigns still.

Israeli police say they‚Äôve frozen multiple accounts on the world‚Äôs largest cryptocurrency exchange Binance that they believed were related to Hamas.  Hamas solicited cryptocurrency donations to the accounts online following the group‚Äôs surprise attack on Israel last weekend, according to Israeli police.

‚ÄúWith the outbreak of the conflict, Hamas initiated a fundraising campaign on various social networks, urging the public to deposit cryptocurrencies into its accounts,‚Äù a police statement said. ‚ÄúThe Police Cyber Unit and Ministry of Defense immediately took action to locate and freeze these accounts, with the assistance of the Binance crypto exchange, in order to divert the funds to the state treasury.‚Äù

It is not clear if the Binance accounts financed any part of Hamas recent attacks on Israel, or how much money was moved to Israel‚Äôs state treasury.

Digital wallets linked to Hamas received $41 million between August 2021 and June 2023, the Wall Street Journal reports, citing Tel Aviv crypto analytics firm BitOK.

Donors and recipients of certain types of cryptocurrency exchanged on Binance can be anonymous, but new developments in blockchain tracking and identity mandates are allowing authorities to track and seize more illicit exchanges.

A Binance spokesperson said their team has been working ‚Äúaround the clock, to support ongoing efforts to combat terror financing.‚Äù Hamas is designated as a foreign terrorist organization in Israel and the U.S.

14-year-old Klondike entered Riverside Shelter in May as a severely matted and flea-infested stray. After he was euth-listed, we put a hold on him and began arranging for his exit. We put out a plea for volunteers to do his freedom ride, which Jayne Kleinfeld saw while she was sitting on the Frosted Faces Foundation‚Äôs porch while waiting for her Frosted Face Beck and Charlie‚Äôs vet appointments. She offered to go get him and brought him down to us safely.

Jayne found that she couldn‚Äôt stop thinking about Klondike and came back to scoop him up for a Fling that same week! After their two-week Fling was up and she brought him back to Frosted Faces Foundation, she was completely devastated and cried every day! She missed him so much and ultimately realized that she couldn‚Äôt imagine not being his family. Jayne made it official and adopted Klondike! Here is an update on how he is doing: 

‚ÄúKlondike has settled in fantastically! I initially took him on a Fling before I adopted him, and within a few hours of being here, he had become my shadow and was following me everywhere. His favorite food is everything, and his favorite activity is napping! He's pretty low-energy and just enjoys sleeping for most of the day, which means that he fits in perfectly with my Frosted Face's Beck and Charlie (formerly Domingo)!"

Song Story: ‚ÄúHalf Here‚Äù
One of our first writing sessions after our first child was born, I looked at Daniel and said, ‚ÄúI can‚Äôt do this right now. I am literally half here.‚Äù He proposed that I instead go take some time and write about that‚Ä¶

Early motherhood has been a challenging war of interests. Even two and 3/4 years into this parenthood journey, I feel constantly torn in two. If I am working, I feel like I am neglecting my children, whose needs are (understandably) unceasing. If I am tending only to the children I feel as though an important part of me is atrophying. I often feel the loss of this great creative joint effort Daniel and I used to regularly share and enjoy together. To be a mother with additional vocation is to be in perpetual conflict. 

Our culture says you can have it all as a woman, but I am honestly not sure if that is true, or at least the ‚Äúit all‚Äù that everyone keeps referring to comes with some small print that I didn‚Äôt see when considering this path of family expansion. And of course there is this other factor, the biological one: wherein a great percentage of my brain power and life force is daily siphoned off without my knowledge, employed in the work of milk production and body repair, slackened by sleep deprivation and internal conflict.

Let the record reflect that I adore our children. They are beautiful individuals with intricate personalities and I have so much respect for who they already are and who they are becoming. I even enjoy them much of the time. I think it is precisely my appreciation of them and my desire for them to have the space to expand that makes focusing on other things so difficult for me. FOMO is also a real factor.üòÇ

The song ‚ÄúHalf Here‚Äù was one that felt like it wrote itself. It proceeded from the ether, each line seeming to lead to the next until it was done. Afterward I just felt grateful to have a song that so fully expressed where I was at that moment in my life (currently, too?), and yet one that still allowed me to feel alive and lovely when singing it. Daniel sat down with me afterward and came up with that
delightful guitar part that keeps it feeling breezy the whole way through.

The true test of a man is not where he stands during times of comfort and leisure, but where he stands during times of conflict and controversy. You‚Äôll see if you are made of that stuff when it gets rough.

It‚Äôs #NationalComingOutDay.
There were myriad reasons the journey for this little boy was hard. Community, cultural, religious expectations.
And every year I talk about how, despite advances, it‚Äôs still so hard for so many, and impossible for others to consider coming out.
And that‚Äôs still so true. And if you‚Äôre reading and not ready or not able, we‚Äôre here when you are or can.
But I‚Äôm also absorbed, as most are, in the horrid conflict happening in real time and thinking mostly of the gay and queer Jews and Palestinians I know. And how many of them are being asked to account for the terrible actions of others.
It‚Äôs a reminder that gay and queer are a part of us, but so are so many other things. And so many around the world can‚Äôt even consider their queerness because of more basic threats to their lives, worlds and existence.
I don‚Äôt have answers, but I do know the strange social media jockeying and posturing requiring the most exhaustive series of caveats to state even the most basic care for equality and human dignity isn‚Äôt helping Jews and Palestinians here and certainly not any in the path of the destruction.
Hold close those you love who are hurting. Be equally willing to stand against visceral acts of terrorism and the slow suffocation of human dignity.
And to my LGBTQ+ friends and family who choose to be visible in a time of continued vitriol and increased danger - I admire and applaud you.
We must all do what we can, where we can.

The reports I am receiving from Israel and Gaza are horrifying. It‚Äôs absolutely saddening to see the level of carnage and death on both sides. War should never be an option, and it‚Äôs time we shift our focus from political and religious agendas to the human faces behind the statistics.
 
There's no justification, no ideology, and no belief system that can legitimise the abduction and killing of civilians including children. Such acts defy the basic principles of humanity. It goes against the faith we profess and must be vehemently opposed by everybody. 

Violence begets only more violence. We have a moral responsibility to advocate an immediate cessation of violence and encourage reconciliation. Both Israelis and Palestinians have ancient roots in the region.
To achieve peace, reconciliation and restitution must be the cornerstone. The two sides must find common ground, heal wounds, and acknowledge the humanity in one another. Seeing people as humans will minimise collateral damage and foster understanding and kindness. 

The world has witnessed enough suffering; it's time for the cycle of violence to cease. It‚Äôs time to build bridges and to ensure that future generations might know a life not defined by conflict and death but by harmony, tolerance, and peace.

My thoughts and prayers are with those affected by the ongoing conflict. I pray for God to calm the storms of war and touch the people‚Äôs hearts to create a new path to peace and harmonious co-existence in Israel and Palestine.

üìñ ‚Ä¢ The Fastest Way to Fall is a slow-burn, friends-to-lovers romance in which Britta, a journalist at a lifestyle site, signs up for a fitness app as part of a work project and is paired with Wes, the app‚Äôs CEO, as her online fitness coach. ‚Å£
üí≠ ‚Ä¢  I really love the fat representation in this novel. Britta is fat and happy with her body. She looks good and knows it, yet decides to try a fitness routine to feel better. There is no real talk of diets for Britta in sight. There is simply a fat woman happy and confident in with the way she looks. I thought Williams did a great job showing that Britta‚Äôs contentment with her body did not exclude her from feeling society‚Äôs anti-fatness.

However, I wish I could say that the rest of The Fastest Way to Fall worked as well for me. I could not get past the very contrived plot. When Britta and Wes begin communicating, I had a hard time believing the unnatural progression. Their flirting and eventual meeting up was so awkward and uncomfortable. There was no way I could lose myself in the flirtation that felt like a creepy middle school fantasy.

‚Å£The main conflict in The Fastest Way to Fall is that neither protagonist fully discloses their job to the other. Normally, this would not be the biggest deal (although it would be super unusual), but how they meet is centered around their professional roles. The ethical issues with their jobs stressed me out. The fact that it did not worry the character‚Äôs more seemed unrealistic. Neither tried to immediately address the situation, despite there being an easy solution, and instead waited until shit hit the fan. At that point, I was annoyed with both characters for making stupid choices that they knew would end poorly. A majority of the conflict could have been easily avoided by making responsible decisions in the interest of their careers and livelihoods. Here‚Äôs some real talk for Coming Out Day.

Coming out is an expression of authenticity, and as such, it deserves every respect and honor!

It‚Äôs not easy to claim your truth‚Äîin any way. 

We‚Äôre programmed to not rock the boat, to be homogenous, to blend in.

And when we don‚Äôt do that‚Äîwhen we stand out‚Äîit‚Äôs dangerous.

There‚Äôs a scientific reason for this:

We evolved as a communal species, and as such, we‚Äôre literally hardwired for connection with each other.

In order to foster that connection, we try to have as much in common with others as possible, thus helping us avoid conflict and rejection.

Rejection literally feels to our Autonomic Nervous System like a very real threat of death.

Think about it: if, when we were tribal people hunting and gathering in groups, you were exiled from the community, your ass was gonna get eaten by a sabertooth tiger. You were definitely, 100% gonna die. RIP, you.

That‚Äôs how intensely we feel the threat of rejection.

So coming out, which already puts you in a social minority, is a scary fucking thing, even if everyone in your life is supportive.

Here‚Äôs the kicker: if you‚Äôre not out, a day like today can leave you feeling like maybe you‚Äôre not living authentically.

And watching people you know in your community come out and celebrate their own authenticity might make you feel a different kind of rejection and other-ness.

It might feel like a no-win scenario, but hear me out‚Ä¶

So what if you‚Äôre not out yet?! You have your reasons, and that‚Äôs good enough for you, so it should be good enough for everyone.

If the most authentic thing for you to do in this moment is not come out on National Coming Out Day, then don‚Äôt!

If the most authentic thing for you to do is come out to the people you can trust and the people you feel comfortable with and not all of your 20k TikTok followers, then great! Do that!

Just whatever you do, try not to shame yourself.

Please don‚Äôt shame yourself for your queerness. You‚Äôre beautiful and perfect and Divine.

Please don‚Äôt shame yourself for coming out or not coming out. You‚Äôre beautiful and perfect and Divine.

Let‚Äôs just start there. üè≥Ô∏è‚Äçüåàü§ç
